<HEADLINE> Kuwait not Support Military Attack on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah said here today that Kuwait does
not support military actions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We do not support any military measures against Iraq," said
Sabah following a meeting with the Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak this morning.
</P>
<P>
But he urged Baghdad to fully comply with the United Nations
Security Council resolutions to avoid military strike.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he denied that the four-way military maneuvers
simultaneously held in Kuwait is directed against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I am sorry that their timing came in such circumstances. But
the exercises have no relation whatsoever with the Iraqi crisis,"
</P>
<P>
He said that the joint war games between Kuwait, the United
States, Britain and Italy had been scheduled two months ago to
follow the maneuvers in Egypt in October.
</P>
<P>
Iraq last Thursday expelled six Americans working for the
United Nations Special Commission for eliminating Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction. And the U.S. and Britain is sending the
aircraft carriers of "George Washington" and "Invincible" to the
Gulf to join the USS Nimitz already there.
</P>
<P>
Sabah also denied that the U.S. has asked to use Kuwaiti
facilities in the event of military strikes against Iraq which
invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had urged Arab countries, particularly Gulf countries, not
to let the U.S. use their military bases to launch strikes against
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Sabah, also Kuwaiti First Deputy Prime Minister, arrived Egypt
Saturday for a two-day visit. He will later travel to Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, he delivered a message from Kuwaiti Emir
Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmed Al-Sabah covering bilateral ties and the
latest developments of the regional situations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
