<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Tennis Rankings System To Be Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The rankings system in men's
tennis will be changed from the year 2,000 to an annual points
race with every player starting at zero in January, a top ATP Tour
official said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mark Miles, chief executive officer of the ATP Tour ruling the
men's circuit, said in Hanover that the new system, signalling the
end of the complicated current method under which the players
carry their points from one year to the next, was one of several
changes.
</P>
<P>
In a news conference during the ATP Tour world championship in
Hanover, Miles said a new super league of seven events would be
launched and the year-end championships would be reshaped.
</P>
<P>
All the changes would be introduced from the year 2,000, he
addded.
</P>
<P>
Discussions are under way with the International Tennis
Federation (ITF) and the Women's Tennis Association (WTA) over the
changes and the possibility of including the women in the super
league tournaments and the season-ending event, Miles continuted.
</P>
<P>
The seven events in the super league will be Indian Wells, Key
Biscayne, the Stuttgart and Paris indoor tournaments, two European
clay events and one North American hardcourt event to be
designated, he said.
</P>
<P>
The rankings will take into account the four grand slams, the
super seven and seven other tournaments of lesser importance,
Miles added.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the players will start every year with zero
points instead of having to defend the points they won the
previous year should make the sport more interesting to follow, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The world championship will stay in Hanover and stick to its
current format until 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
