<HEADLINE> Russia to Take "Active Steps" in Resolving Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today said his country will "take the most active steps" to
peacefully resolve the Iraq crisis around nuclear inspection.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made the remark this morning during a 20-minute
telephone conversation with his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton over
their "hot line," the Russian presidential press service said.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed that the international community
should settle the Iraq crisis through active diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
They also emphasized, according to the press service, the
importance of regular contacts between Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The Russian and U.S. presidents instructed the two officials,
who held a telephone talk before the two top leaders'
conversation, to keep discussing pressing issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
