<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemeni PM Leaves for Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Prime Minister Farag
Saeed Bin Ghanim left here today for Paris to participate in a
Paris Club meeting scheduled for November 18 in a bid to deal with
Yemeni debts owed to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Sanaa, the Yemeni prime minister told Saba News
Agency of Yemen that his visit to France is intended to get a
large part of these debts written off and the rest of them
rescheduled, in accordance with the resolutions passed at the
Paris Club meeting held in the Italian city of Naples.
</P>
<P>
Ghanem said that the Yemeni government is optimistic a
breakthrough in this issue could be achieved because of the
remarkable success in Yemen's economic reform programs, the
growing confidence of the international community in the Yemeni
economy and financial support given by donor states and
international organizations to Yemen.
</P>
<P>
He added that his visit to Paris will be a good opportunity for
him to hold talks with a number of French officials and economists
on ways of promoting bilateral cooperation between the two
countries, especially in the economic domain.
</P>
<P>
Yemen hoped to be exempted from 90 percent of the its
6.7-billion-U.S. dollar debts owed to Russia, and that the rest of
these debts would be rescheduled, expecting Yemen's remaining
debts to range between 350 million and 370 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most of the debts owed by Yemen to Russia date back to the
1980s when the southern part of Yemen got large quantities of arms
from Russia during the civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
