<HEADLINE> Chirac, Jospin Express Condolences on Marchais' Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin have expressed condolences over
the death of Georges Marchais, the former French Communist Party
(PCF) leader who died of heart disease this morning in Paris.
</P>
<P>
"I learned with sadness the disappearance of Georges Marchais.
I knew him well, and I could have measured the strength and
sincerity of his convictions," said Chirac in a written message of
condolences, in which the president called Marchais "a real figure
who is gone."
</P>
<P>
Chirac said Marchais had "marked profoundly and for long years
the history of the French Communist Party as well as the whole of
our political scenery."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jospin said that Marchais was "a man of the
people who become one of the strongest, highest in color and most
known figures in our political life."
</P>
<P>
"Georges Marchais will remain as a vigorous figure of the
communist movement in the heart of the left of these last
decades," said Jospin in a communique.
</P>
<P>
The French Communist Party is flying the national flag of
France and the red flag at half mast today at its headquarters in
the Colonel Fabien Square in Paris to mourn Marchais, who was
general secretary of the PCF from 1972 until 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
