<HEADLINE> Agency: U.S. Gas Emissions Will Be Worse Than Thought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The emissions of carbon
dioxide and other heat-trapping gases from energy use will grow
faster than expected in the United States in the next few years,
the U.S. Energy Department said.
</P>
<P>
This would make it more difficult for the United States to live
up to President Clinton's proposal to cap emissions of these gases
at 1990 levels over the next 10 to 15 years, the Washington Post
pointed out in a report of the annual energy outlook by the Energy
Information Administration today.
</P>
<P>
The nation's economic growth would be slightly higher than
previously estimated, electricity would be cheaper and fuel prices
would not change, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, more oil will be used because of an increase of more
cars with more horsepowers, and more people travelling by plane.
</P>
<P>
These factors are likely to increase emissions of greenhouse
gases, produced largely through the use of fossil fuels like oil
and coal.
</P>
<P>
Carbon emissions in 1990 were 1,336 million metric tons, the
agency said. If no action was taken, the number would climb to
1,722 million by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Jay E. Hakes, head of the Energy Information Administration was
quoted by the Post as saying that there were technologies to
reduce carbon output, but no new inventions or improvements
of existing devices appeared likely to be in wide enough use by
2010 to drop the forecast much. 
</P>
</TEXT>
