<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Admits Mishandling Formula One Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said today he accepts that the government mishandled the row
over the Formula One (F1) tobacco sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
He said in a BBC Television interview, "I take full
responsibility and apologize for that." He also conceded that the
matter "hasn't been handled well."
</P>
<P>
The Labor government announced on November 5 that it would
exempt Formula One motor racing from a ban on tobacco sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
The government's trouble began following the revelation that
the Labor Party had received a donation of 1 million pounds (1.7
million US dollars) from F1 boss Bernie Ecclestone before the
general election on May 1 and that it had offered the party more
money after the election.
</P>
<P>
Blair said today that the government should have admitted that
it had received the donation more than a week ago rather than
allow information to drip out by damaging leaks.
</P>
<P>
"It should not have come out in drips and drabs and we should
have focused on this earlier," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he pledged that the harsh lessons of the episode had
been learnt and stressed his government's commitment to higher
ethical standards.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the F1 row had been the government's worst
since the general election and it could herald the end of the
Labor government's six-month political honeymoon with the
country's voters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
