<HEADLINE> French Communist Party to Hold Marchais' Funeral Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The French Communist Party (PCF)
will hold the funeral of its former leader Georges Marchais
Thursday in Val-de-Marne south of Paris, where he was parliament
deputy from 1973 to 1997, said the PCF press bureau today.
</P>
<P>
Marchais, general secretary of the PCF from 1972 until 1994,
died of heart disease today in hospital in Paris at the age of 77.
</P>
<P>
The PCF National Bureau said the death of Marchais caused pain
and was an immense loss for the party.
</P>
<P>
"It is not time... to evaluate the contribution Georges
(Marchais) had brought to our party and to France. This evaluation
will be done," said the National Bureau in a declaration
transmitted by Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
It said that Marchais "became a communist for doing the good
and for serving the cause of the humble, from whom he came. He had
never departed from this choice," said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
Helene Luc, president of the PCF group in the French Senate,
said that Marchais "marked the history of France for more than a
quarter of the century by assuming major responsibilities in a
period of great upheavals."
</P>
<P>
In Villejuif, a city south of Paris which is administered by
the PCF, many government officials and employees remained in a
state of shock after hearing the unexpected death of Marchais.
</P>
<P>
The French national flag and the red flag were flying at half
mast today at the office building of the local section of the PCF
there, while people gave their signatures at books of condolences
at the City Hall, where Marchais was once the mayor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
