<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Encourages Employee Ownership Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government and
the private sector should come up with employee ownership schemes
in line with world trends of securing equitable distribution of
wealth among the workers, a minister of state has said.
</P>
<P>
Officially closing a two-day employee ownership schemes and
sub-contracting seminar today in Bulawayo, the country's second
largest city, minister of state for parastatals and
indigenisation Cephas Msipa said such schemes would economically
empower the majority of black people, helping the indigenisation
process.
</P>
<P>
"Let's therefore work together with private sector and the
government to ensure that we put in place schemes which are
meaningful both to the workers as direct beneficiaries and to the
general cause of indigenisation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said previous experiences from developed countries had
shown that employee share ownership impacted positively on labour
relations and productivity, especially where the benefits were
significant because the worker was also an employer.
</P>
<P>
He commended some big private sector companies that were
already implementing or considering employee ownership schemes
while urging those that had not done so to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Msipa said the government was finalising mechanisms
to sub-contract some non-core functions and encouraged indigenous
business people to play an active role.
</P>
<P>
He also criticised indigenous business people of sometimes
failing to perform up to standard and implored them to do a
perfect job to avoid a situation where the government would be
forced to protect poor-performers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
