<HEADLINE> Demand for Cellular Phone Likely to Drop in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The demand for cellular
phones in Tanzania is likely to drop in 1998, when an ambitious
communications rehabilitation program is completed, Observer
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The National Telecommunications Reconstruction Program, due
for completion by December next year, will increase the
distribution of telephones and improve the network performance at
a cheaper price, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The 400,000 US dollars program, almost 75 percent complete,
involves the installation of ultra modern digital swithches and
superhighways at various points in the country, the construction
of buildings to house telephone equipment and ugrading of
satellites linking Tanzania with outside world.
</P>
<P>
The program is being implemented by Tanzania
Telecommunications Company Limited (TTCL) and seven donors,
including the World Bank, the European Union and the African
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
It has already availed switching capacities of 62,450 Median
Distribution Framework (MDF) pairs and 61,580 lines so far,
reducing tremendously the number of customers on the waiting
lists in seven towns of the country, according to TTCL Public
Relations Manager, Issa Semtawa.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the entire project, an additional number of
137,758 exchange lines and 192,240 MDF pairs respectively will be
available enabling clients get services as they supply.
</P>
<P>
Telephone density would stand at 1.2 above the target of 1.0
set for the year 2000, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
