<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes Iraqi Crisis Contained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today voiced hope that the current crisis between Iraq and
the United States will be contained through political action.
</P>
<P>
He said at a press conference that Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz is due here Monday to hold talks with Arab League
Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid on the regional
tensions.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a chance to discuss with the Iraqi official the
latest developments in the area," said the minister, who will
also meet Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Aziz's visit to Egypt is part of a North African tour, which
also includes Libya, Tunisia, Algeria and Morocco, to explain
Iraq's view on the tensions.
</P>
<P>
It is evident that the Iraqis are frustrated and desperate over
the slow progress in lifting the crippling sanctions imposed on it
by the United Nations Security Council since its invasion of
Kuwait in August 1990, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The frustration and hardships of the Iraqi people should be put
into consideration while regarding prospects of cooperation
between the Iraqi government and the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) for eliminating its weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has sent two
messages to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, and held contacts with
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to discuss the situations.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, accusing the Americans of controlling the U.N. weapons
inspection teams and prolonging the lifting of the sanctions,
kicked them out last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM must verify that Iraq has destroyed its weapons of
mass destruction before the U.N. Security Council will decide to
lift the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of Iraq's action, the United States and Britain are
sending their aircraft carriers of "George Washington" and
"Invincible" to the Gulf to join the USS Nimitz already there.
</P>
