<HEADLINE> UNITA Urged to Fulfill Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 16 (Xinhua ) -- The Angolan Social Democratic
Party (PSDA) urged the former rebel party here today to cooperate
with government in re-establishing local governments in areas
under its control.
</P>
<P>
Nzuzi Nsumbo, deputy chairman of PSDA, one of the major
parties in the country, made the statement at a ceremony marking
the eighth anniversary of the founding of the party.
</P>
<P>
He demanded UNITA, the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, to offer the actual number of army it now
has to the UN supervision team, so to facilitate the disarmament
of UNITA according to the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Nsumbo said that the scheduled meeting between Angolan
President Eduardo Dos Santos and UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi by
the end of the month is crucial to the future of the country.
</P>
<P>
The two sides should narrow down their differences and gain
new impetus to the peace process so as to speed up the peace
process in the country and concentrate Angola's attention on
rebuilding, Nsumbo said.
</P>
<P>
He said that his party believes that the national unity and
reconciliation government, parliament members and UN
representatives in Angola have made great effort to the peace
process in the country, adding that UNITA's refusal to allow
local governments to be re-established in its areas, has
undermined the interests of other parties.
</P>
<P>
PSDA fully supports UN's sanctions over UNITA, which would
press it to fulfill the Lusaka peace agreement, Nsumbo said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the government to continue collecting the arms
scattered among the citizens for the security of the country.
