<HEADLINE> U.S. State Secretary Arrives in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright arrived in Kuwait within a four-country
Gulf tour aimed at rallying support of Gulf Arab allies for
U.S. military Build-up in the region.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here from Manama, Bahrain, after first
attending the inauguration session of the Economic Conference of
the Middle East and North Africa this morning in Doha, Qatar and
she will also go to Saudi Arabia tonight.
</P>
<P>
Upon her arrival here, Albright immediately held talks with
Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah and Crown Prince
and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdellah Al-Salem Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
She is in the region with two preoccupations mainly to
rally support to confront Iraq in a possible military showdown
over the latest crisis resulting from Iraq's expulsion of
American arms inspectors, besides ensuring success of the Doha
economic conference.
</P>
<P>
Washington and Baghdad are locked in a confrontation over
Iraq's expulsion this week of Americans working as part of
the U.N. Special Commission in charge of verifying weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Albright's spokesman James Rubin said in Berne before the
American state secretary setting out for the region that "at a
time like this it is very important for us to consult with our
friends in the Gulf" because those are the "countries that are
the front-line states."
</P>
<P>
Albright said that she started this shuttle tour of this
region because "we have a mutual interests in the stability
of the region."
</P>
<P>
Albright made it clear in Doha that Washington was
determined that Iraq not be allowed to block the U.N. mission
although her country was making every effort to end the
crisis through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday ordered the aircraft George
Washington to rush to the Gulf region to join another carrier
battle group consisted of Nimitz aircraft carrier and several
other warships that are already on station.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Central Command chief Anthony Zinni visited Kuwait
Friday to hold discussions of contingency plans which Albright
might now ask for permission to activate, diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
However, observers here believe that it would be much more
difficult for the United States to build a coalition both inside
and outside the region to support a military action against Iraq
comparing with the Gulf War in 1991 when an allied force led by
the U.S. liberated Kuwait from Iraqi seven-month occupation.
</P>
<P>
They said if Clinton orders a punitive military strike, he
risks splitting the already shaky international coalition that
has kept Saddam Hussein more or less in check since the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Russia, France and many Arab countries including regional
heavyweight Egypt are against military action against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
