<HEADLINE> Israeli, US Defense Ministers on Hot Line Over Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 16 (Xinhua) -- As standoff between Iraq
and the United States continues growing, Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai has a discussion with his U.S. counterpart
William Cohen over hot line on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai discussed with Cohen a variety of issues, prominently
the current Iraqi crisis, Israeli state television Channel I
reported today. This was the first time that Mordechai used the
hot line since it was installed 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Army has been closely monitoring the ongoing showdown
between Iraq and the U.S. over the weapon inspection, but it
believed that the possibility of an Iraqi missile strike against
Israel is little in case an Iraqi-U.S. military confrontation
breaks out.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Mordechai called on the public not to be panic
about the current crisis in the Gulf, citing the situation was
different from 7 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military officials noted that while Iraq has only left
a small number of missile launchers as the result of the weapon
inspection conducted by the United Nations, Israel has also
acquired more advanced anti-missile systems.
</P>
<P>
Military analysts were quoted by Israel Radio as saying that
even a military conflict breaks out in the Gulf, the American
strike is expected to be limited and so would be the Iraqi
response, which means Israel is unlikely to be attacked.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Army and citizens do not risk taking any
chance as their memory is still alive about the missile attacks
launched against Tel Aviv by Iraq in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Army's Home Command, which is in charge of civil
defense, has issued notifications to citizens to remind them of
updating their masks and getting new ones for new babies.
</P>
<P>
Mask distribution centers across the country have been busy in
dealing with an increased number of anxious citizens who either
come to replace the old masks or to get new ones for babies.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem's Mask Distribution Center, a long queue was formed
this afternoon. Those waiting to get masks said they were convinced
to come by the hectic media report about the crisis although they
have been notified by the Army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
