<HEADLINE> Israeli Intransigence Obstructs Regional Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister
for Development Jawad Anani said here today that Israeli
government's intransigence is obstructing the economic development
process in the Middle East and North Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian official made the remarks when addressing today's
inaugural session of the fourth Middle East and North Africa
Economic Conference here.
</P>
<P>
The setback of negotiations along the Palestinian track, the
delay in redeployment of Israeli troops, the continuing
construction of settlements in Arab land, the denial of legitimate
rights of the Arab inhabitants in Jerusalem and other acts have
turned the economic dream into a mirage of skepticism and doubts,
said Anani.
</P>
<P>
Anani, who is leading Jordan's delegation to the Doha economic
conference, added that the Middle East and North African countries
have not succeeded so far in creating an economic zone due to
continuing tensions in the region.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the various aspects of tension and long years
of warfare have driven away investments, technology and long-term
projects.
</P>
<P>
Anani denounced Israel's hegemony and tight control over
Palestinian economy, asserting that liberating and freeing
Palestinian economy, and unleashing its potential, has become
preconditions of opening up channels of cooperation based on
equality and mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East and North Africa, as a region, standing at the
threshold of the 21st century, finds itself incapable of exerting
the required energy to catch up with international economy and
other economic groupings, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the countries of the region to exert much
greater efforts than ever before, to narrow the gap with world
development rates.
</P>
<P>
Anani emphasized that without cooperation, the countries of the
region will not solve their basic problems, namely, the problem of
water, food production, creation of job opportunities, raising
people's standards of education and health, build-up of
competitive production capabilities, and providing the appropriate
atmosphere for creativity in administering civilian and military
resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reiterated his country's appreciation of the Arab
League initiative for the establishment of an Arab free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
Before the inauguration session of the conference, Jordan
signed here today a U.S.-backed agreement with Israel for the
establishment of a distinct industrial zone on the territory of
Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
