<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Jet Fighter Reappears over Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOGOS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A Jet fighter of the West
African Peacekeeping Force (ecomog) returned to Sierra Leone
today, leading to sporadic firing in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG Alpha fighter plane flew over Freetown at around
1:00 this afternoon and at about the same time anti-aircraft
firing was heard from the ground.
</P>
<P>
The jet fighter then disappeared without returning fire, the
British Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Before 2:30 pm, the national radio announced that just a few
seconds ago, the ECOMOG aircraft fired several times at the house
of a former minister in one suburban town of Freetown, but no
casualty was reported.
</P>
<P>
Some people reportedly said the ECOMOG plane did open fire at
their houses, while some others said they were not too sure where
the gunfire came from, suggesting it may be from the forces of
the military junta from the ground.
</P>
<P>
At another town where ECOMOG jet fighter flew over, people
were angry, saying that it violated the peace accord signed last
month in Conakry, Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord between west African foreign ministers and
the junta calls for ceasefire between the junta forces and ECOMOG
which has been deployed in Sierra Leone to enforce a sub-regional
and United Nations sanction since coupists overthrew the
legitimate government in may this year.
</P>
<P>
This is the first that ECOMOG fighter plane was reported to
return to Freetown and open fire since the fruitless talks
between the peacekeepers and the junta ended last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day talks was designed to work out modalities to
implement the Conakry Peace Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two parties differed over a number of major issues
including whether the Sierra Leonean army should be disarmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
