<HEADLINE> Russia, Ukraine Reach Free Added Tax Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and his visiting Ukrainian counterpart, Leonid Kuchma, today
reached an agreement on fully abolishing value added tax on
production supplies between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the agreement initiated
by the Russian president was reached during a stroll of the two
presidents immediately after Kuchma arrived in Russia this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of state expressed satisfaction with the work
done by a Russian government delegation that was in Kiev on
November 14.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he had discussed the results of the trip in detail
with First Deputy Premier Anatoly Chubais and spoke highly of the
agreement reached on the problem with Ukraine supplying sugar to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
At today's informal meeting held at Rus, a country residence
outside Moscow, the two sides also focused on ways of implementing
the agreements reached during Yeltsin's visit to Kiev in May this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax quoted a spokesman for Yeltsin as saying that the
two sides' attention was mainly paid to the implementation of the
Friedship Treaty, which has not been ratified yet but is already
considered to be a guiding document for Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The presidents also discussed economic problems and mapped out
further cooperation within the framework of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
It was reported Yeltsin and Kuchma agreed to expand political
contacts and adjust the mechanism of meetings between the
presidents and premiers of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The talks will continue Monday, and a joint communique will be
issued outlining the agreements that have been reached, the
Interfax said. 
