<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Big Commercial Bank Declares Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Takushoku Bank in
Hokkaido declared bankruptcy today because of massive
non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
This is the first national commercial bank to go bankrupt in
the country.
</P>
<P>
One of Japan's top 10 commercial banks, it will have to
transfer its business in Hokkaido to the North Pacific Bank,
reports here said. But they did not say if it has found banks to
take over its business in other areas.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka and Bank of Japan Governor
Yasuo Matsushita said all deposits at Hokkaido Takushoku will
be protected.
</P>
<P>
The central bank will extend special loans without collateral
to Hokkaido Takusyoku until it shuts down its operations, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Sadamasa Kawatani, president of the Hokkaido Takushoku, told a
press conference in Sapporo that his bank has faced difficulties
in procuring funds due to its bad loans, loss of creditability and
the fall in share prices.
</P>
<P>
The amount of disclosed bad loans held by Hokkaido Takushoku
Bank was 930 billion yen (7.4 billion U.S. dollars) as of March 31
this year, the end of fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
In April, Hokkaido Takushoku announced plans to merge with the
regional Hokkaido Bank for survival. But the latter suspected that
the former's nonperforming loans were far larger than it had
admitted.
</P>
<P>
In October, the two banks announced they postponed the merger
plans.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here viewed this bankruptcy as symbolizing the
collapse of the Finance Ministry's so-called convoy system, which
protects weaker financial institutions with a web of
administrative regulations and guidance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
