<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists Killed in Bus Hijack in Upper Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Two to 15 foreign tourists were
killed and 22 others wounded as unidentified gunmen hijacked a
tour bus in the tourist town of Luxor in southern Egypt Monday and
exchanged gunfire with police, said diplomatic sources.
</P>
<P>
One hijacker has reportedly been killed by police which are in
pursuit of the five to eight gunmen, who are believed still in the
bus with the hostages.
</P>
<P>
According to tourist guides on site, the bus was carrying
Japanese, American and German tourists when it was hijacked by a
number of attackers and driven to the Valley of Queens and Kings
which houses hundreds of Pharaonic tombs.
</P>
<P>
So far there is no claim of responsibility for the attack. But
speculations have it that the Islamic militants that have been
fighting a five-year violent campaign against the Egyptian secular
government was to blame.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists, so far undeterred by the violent waves
sweeping the south, always visit Luxor, one of Egypt's top tourist
attractions lying 560 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
In the previous attack targeting foreign tourists, nine Germans
and an Egyptian drive were killed on September 18 when gunmen
opened fire on a bus in front of the Egyptian Antiquities Museum
in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 3,000 have been killed in the violence, mostly
policemen, terrorists, tourists and civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
