<HEADLINE> Urgent: 23 Killed in Tourist Bus Hijacking in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Altogether 23 people, including
11 foreign tourists and 11 Egyptians, were killed as unidentified
gunmen shot at and later hijacked a tour bus in a southern
Egyptian archeological resort his morning.
</P>
<P>
One hijacker was shot dead in an exchange of gunfire with
police in pursuit of the five to eight gunmen, who are believed
still in the bus with the hostages, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to tourist guides on site, the bus was carrying
Japanese, American and German tourists when it was hijacked by a
number of attackers and driven to the Valley of Queens and Kings
which houses hundreds of Pharaonic tombs.
</P>
<P>
So far there is no claim of responsibility for the attack. But
speculations have it that the Islamic militants that have been
fighting a five-year violent campaign against the Egyptian secular
government were to blame.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists, so far undeterred by the violent waves
sweeping the south since 1992, never fail to visit Luxor, a top
Egyptian tourist attraction lying 560 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
In the previous attack targeting foreign tourists, nine
Germans and an Egyptian drive were killed on September 18 when
gunmen opened fire on a bus in front of the Egyptian Antiquities
Museum in Cairo. The two assailants were sentenced to death on
October 30.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 3,000 have been killed in the violence, mostly
policemen, terrorists, tourists and civilians. 
</P>
