<HEADLINE> 6 Hijackers Killed in Egypt's Tourist Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- All six known terrorists that
hijacked an international tourist bus in the southern Egyptian
tourist city of Luxor this morning have been killed, said an
Interior Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
An Interior Ministry official without identifying him said
that one terrorist was killed in the crossfire with the police
and five others were shot in the following pursuit carried out by
the police. He unidentified the six men as "terrorists" without
giving more details.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian TV, breaking its normal broadcast, inserted the
announcement on the second attack on foreign tourists in Egypt
in two months.
</P>
<P>
Local Middle East News Agency reported earlier that 22
foreigners and Egyptians were killed but later corrected it to
22 wounded, 11 foreign tourists and 11 Egyptians, as unidentified
gunmen shot at and later hijacked a tour bus in Luxor.
</P>
<P>
The wounded were flown to the Egyptian capital of Cairo for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
According to tourist guides on site, the bus was carrying
Japanese, American and German tourists when it was hijacked by a
number of attackers and driven to the Valley of Queens on the
west bank of the Nile, which houses hundreds of Pharaonic tombs.
</P>
<P>
So far no one has claimed responsibility for the attack. But
speculations have it that the Islamic militants that have been
fighting a five-year violent campaign against the Egyptian secular
government were to blame.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists, though a prime target of the terror campaign,
so far have been undeterred by the violent waves sweeping the
south and never fail to visit Luxor, a top Egyptian tourist
attraction lying 560 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
In the previous attack targeting foreign tourists, nine
Germans and an Egyptian drive were killed on September 18 when
gunmen opened fire on a bus in front of the Egyptian Antiquities
Museum in Cairo. The two assailants were sentenced to death on
October 30.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 3,000 have been killed in the violence, mostly
policemen, terrorists, tourists and civilians. 
