<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Urges Preparedness Against Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun,
who also serves as director of the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters, has called on governments at all levels to
reinforce flood control and drought relief capabilities in order
to guarantee a bumper harvest in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Severe summer droughts hit provinces north of the Yangtze River,
with southern regions in China suffering from flooding resulting
from a string of typhoons. Nonetheless, the country recorded a
good grain harvest due to the disaster preparedness campaign which
effectively helped to control droughts and flooding, according to
Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Despite notable progress in overall drought and flood control,
the nation's disaster preparedness system has suffered from
prominent bottlenecks caused by obsolete water conservancy
facilities, inadequate irrigation systems and low-level technology
for flood control.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the central government will improve the
technological level of disaster preparedness facilities, devise a
drought relief and flood control program for the next century, and
increase inputs to water conservation and irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the drought in north China led to a decline in
the autumn grain harvest, and a 30 percent decline in water
reserves in the nation's reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
He called on local governments to remain on alert and increase
the labor force involved in the anti-drought campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
