<HEADLINE> South Korean Currency Falls to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The battered South Korean won
dropped to an all-time low of 1,008.60 against the U.S. dollar on
Monday after the central bank withdrew from the market.
</P>
<P>
After opening at 986.00, the won slid 2.25 percent down from
the previous day's close to 1,008.60, its daily allowable low,
</P>
<P>
Surprised dealers said that the Bank of Korea (BOK) abruptly
stepped out of the market, giving up support to the local currency
and led the dropping past the 1,000 level for the first time.
</P>
<P>
BOK officials said that today's retreat does not mean the
central bank has completely abandoned its intervention policy.
"The bank will step in at any time judged necessary in the
future," they said.
</P>
<P>
Up to this morning, the central bank said it was certain the
won would gradually become firmer against the dollar, reaching 970
by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
A market analyst here interpreted the central bank's move as
being influenced by growing concerns over the nation's declining
foreign-exchange reserve level.
</P>
<P>
The crash was caused by the soaring U.S. dollar and the dim
prospects for the passage of the government's monetary reform
bills through the current National Assembly session, stock traders
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
