<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski said today in Beijing that Poland hopes to restore
economic ties with markets in the Far East, especially with
China.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski made the remarks during a meeting with a group of
over 100 Chinese and Polish entrepreneurs attending today's
economic and trade forum.
</P>
<P>
"My visit to China and this forum prove the point," said
Kwasniewski, adding that economic problems represent a key issue
for discussion with Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski briefed participants on his country's reform and
economic development in recent years, and pointed to the broad
prospects for future development.
</P>
<P>
He touched on bilateral trade contacts and noted that Poland's
imports from China have increased for several years running, while
the volume of exports to China has remained relatively low. He
said the two sides should explore new trade channels in order to
achieve an appropriate trade balance.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show the 1996 bilateral trade volume between the two
countries hit 620 million US dollars, with China recording a
favorable trade balance of 520 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume for the first nine months of this year ended
at 496 million US dollars, with China's export volume standing at
473 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski said the two countries enjoy great potential for
cooperation in wide-ranging sectors, including the power
generation, transportation and environmental protection sectors.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that entrepreneurs from the two countries
will take advantage of the present forum to expand dialog and
mutual understanding, and will participate in in-depth discussions
for specific cooperative projects.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged Chinese entrepreneurs to increase investments in
Poland and join their Polish counterparts in efforts to establish
joint ventures. 
