<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Solicitor on Intellectual Property Rights Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior solicitor stressed
here today that the Patents Ordinance and Registered Designs
Ordinance, which came into force on the eve of Hong Kong's return
to China, marked an important step in its efforts to protect
intellectual property rights (IPR).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar attended by over 130 lawyers and
practitioners of designs and patents, Senior Solicitor of the
Intellectual Property Department Fanny Pang said the two laws
provide the establishment of IPR regimes in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) for the protection of industrial
designs and inventions in line with international standards.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by the Intellectual Property
Department of the SAR government to brief the experts on the two
ordinances and associated registration procedures.
</P>
<P>
"The Patents Ordinance provides for the grant of independent,
standard patents valid for 20 years in Hong Kong," she said.
</P>
<P>
The ordinance also provides for the grant of short-term patents
for a period of eight years. "This form of patent suits inventions
with a short commercial life," Pang pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon the registered design, she said: "Under the
Registered Designs Ordinance, design which appeals to the eye and
is applied to an article by means of an industrial process will be
eligible for registration subject to formality examination."
</P>
<P>
The period of protection of a registered design will initially
be five years, she said. "It may be extended for four periods of
five years each upon payment of the prescribed renewal fee. The
maximum duration of protection will be a total of 25 years."
</P>
<P>
At the one-day seminar, officials from the Intellectual
Property Department also explained in detail the procedures for
the new patents system and registered design registration system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Heads List of Corruption in Africa, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's High Court Judge
Justice Smith today underscored the need to deal with corruption,
saying Zimbabwe is rapidly climbing the ladder of leading corrupt
African countries.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe is heading the list of corruption in Africa and
something has to be done to stop the rot," said Justice Smith at
a three-day Transparency International workshop on national
integrity against corruption in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Smith, who officially opened the workshop, implored
participants to come up with a "concrete" action plan on how to
tackle corruption.
</P>
<P>
By coming up with an action plan, the workshop would have made
a giant step towards developing a national integrity or code of
ethics aimed at curbing corruption, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
Financed by the European Union, the workshop plans to prepare
an outline of a national integrity document focusing on informed
public discussion and national debate.
</P>
<P>
Leading local and international journalists, academics,
politicians and economists are expected to deliver at the
workshop papers on corruption and how it can be eliminated,
particularly in Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
