<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Currency Turmoil to Slow Down Global Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Asian currency turmoil
will slow down the rest of the world's economy in 1998, an
economist predicted here today.
</P>
<P>
Bruce Steinberg, chief economist of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co, said:
"All of the events in this part of the world are sending out a
very powerful contractual impulse into the world's economy."
</P>
<P>
In a special presentation on the financial turmoil in Asia,
Steinberg predicted slower growth, slower corporate earnings,
lower interest rate and less inflation in all economic regions in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth will slow down sharply in Asia, the center of
the financial storm, said the American economist.
</P>
<P>
"Latin America has already caught the Asian flu," he said. As a
direct result of the impact of the Asian crisis, Brazil, which he
had predicted would grow by four percent a month ago, now will not
grow at all in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Growth will also be slower in the United States and Europe.
Steinberg estimated that the currency turbulence in Asia will
reduce the U.S. economic growth by half percent next year. "The
downside risk is so significant, and if anything happens, the U.S.
growth will slow even more than the predicted 2.5 percent," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Corporate earnings will be lower but still positive in the
U.S., he predicted. "The U.S. economy is going to end up in pretty
good shape despite what happened here."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
