<HEADLINE> Swedish Businesses to Use Euro to Attract EMU Clients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Some big Swedish businesses
are prepared to use the euro in their transactions with the
clients in the countries of the European economic and monetary
union (EMU) although Stockholm has decided not to join the single
currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the 21 big businesses surveyed by the newspaper
Today's Business have decided to partially or totally use the euro
for price quotations and account settlements when the new currency
is to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
They include such big names as the Swiss-Swedish engineering
group ABB, telecommunications giant Ericsson, ball bearings
manufacturer SKF, automobile group Volvo and forestry group Stora.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for SKF said his company will settle accounts in
the euro as required by its clients in EMU countries.
</P>
<P>
A monetary policy official with Stora said his company "regards
the use of the euro as a chance to create a common financial
language".
</P>
<P>
Ericsson will reportedly use a dual monetary system to settle
its year-end accounts in 1999: the euro for the general statement
and the Swedish krona for the detailed reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
