<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on Derivatives Trading Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A four-day workshop on
regulatory responses to derivatives trading and other financial
innovations began here today under the aegis of the Southeast
Asian Central Banks (SEACEN) Center, Nepal's official RSS news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the workshop are 20 central bank officials
from Nepal, Indonesia, South Korea, Malaysia, Singapore, Sri Lanka
and China.
</P>
<P>
The workshop aims to enhance the participants' knowledge of
derivatives and their management and make them understand better
the institutional and regulatory framework of the derivatives
markets from regional and global perspectives, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Nepal's Central Bank Governor Satyendra
Pyara Shrestha said the rapid development of financial markets in
the past 20 years could not have been realized without the growth
of derivatives products like futures and options exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He said derivatives markets can pose some specific threats to
the financial systems in countries where regulatory practices lag
significantly behind, but Nepal will no longer be able to afford
to isolate itself from the international financial market.
</P>
<P>
There are no derivatives exchanges in Nepal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
