<HEADLINE> EU GDP Grows by 1.4 Pct in 2nd Quarter of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Strong growth of private
consumption and exports boosted European Union's gross domestic
product (GDP) to a second-quarter increase of 1.4 percent in real
terms.
</P>
<P>
The figure was published today by Eurostat, the
Luxembourg-based statistical arm of the union.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth in the first half of this year has now reached
2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat report said that private consumption rose by 0.9
percent while that of exports surged by 5.4 percent in the
April-June period.
</P>
<P>
Italy posted the biggest rise in exports with 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the EU member states with available data in the Eurostat
report, only Sweden registered a negative growth of 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Finland and the Netherlands led the member states with positive
growths at 2.8 percent and 2.1 percent respectively. 
</P>
