<HEADLINE> South Asia 3-Nation Business Summit to Be Milestone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The one-day South Asia
three-nation business summit, which is scheduled to be held in
Dhaka on November 23, will prove to be a milestone in the
development of economic relations among India, Pakistan and
Bangladesh in particular and in the region in general.
</P>
<P>
This statement was made by Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus
Samad Azad at a press conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the background of the summit, the foreign
minister said that the idea of a three-nation business summit was
put forward by Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina during the
Male Summit of the SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation) heads of state and government in May.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi prime minister extended an invitation to the
prime ministers of India and Pakistan to join her in launching
this initiative to encourage business, trade and investment in the
region, the foreign minister said, adding that the Indian and
Pakistani prime ministers responded enthusiastically to the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
The preparatory work for the summit has been completed by the
national preparatory committee, the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
The summit will BA a one-day affair, he said, "The three prime
ministers and the ministers for foreign affairs, finance and
commerce of the three countries will participate, and business
delegations composed of representatives of leading business houses
of the three countries will also join the summit."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the summit's objectives, the foreign minister said,
"There are several objectives."
</P>
<P>
Close interaction between the private sector and the government
in the three countries would enable mutual understanding of the
view points and challenges faced by each as the region tries to
integrate along a multitude of dimensions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The summit will provide an opportunity to review economic
policies of the three countries and to discuss ways and means to
increase trade, promote joint ventures and investment and the
setting-up of institutional and other linkages among the three
countries to increase economic cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
The interaction between the business and government communities
will send a clear and unconditional signal to the international
community of the strength and the resolve of the governments of
three countries to match investment opportunities and incentives
offered to foreign investors by other developing countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral and Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif will arrive in Dhaka on November 22 and 23
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
