<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Report Blames Unemployment Among </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A draft World Bank study
on the South African labor market has found that the high level
of wages paid to workers contributed to high unemployment among
black workers, the Business Day newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The draft report, which is being circulated in government and
economic think tanks, was written by World Bank economist Peter
Fallon and Nobel economics prize winner Robert Lucas.
</P>
<P>
Their examination of the effect of wages on employment found
that a 10 percent increase in black wages could lead to a 7.1
percent decline in employment.
</P>
<P>
If real black wages had remained constant between 1970 and
1994, black formal employment would have grown at an annual rate
of 1.48 percent instead of the 0.9 percent achieved.
</P>
<P>
In this scenario, employment would have been 13.3 percent
higher than its current level, they said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 46.9 percent of black women and 28.9
percent of black men are unemployed at present.
</P>
<P>
Wage differentials could be resolved, they argued, by removing
discrimination and barriers to mobility rather than increasing
black wages.
</P>
<P>
The report also found that the basic conditions of Employment
Bill, which passed the National Assembly on November 6, would
raise labor costs in sectors already experiencing very high
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The bill provided for a maximum 45-hour working week and other
privileges for workers. It also included a detailed schedule to
reduce the working hours to 40.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey of South Africa's Central Statistics
Service, unemployment in South Africa was getting worse with
employment shrinking 1.5 percent since June last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
