<HEADLINE> Nigeria Cabinet Dissolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State,
General Sani Abacha today announced the dissolution of his
cabinet with immediate effect in an early morning national
broadcast marking the fourth anniversary of his government.
</P>
<P>
As the military government's transition to civil rule has come
to the final state, Abacha explained that it is time to dissolve
the cabinet to enable some ministers who have demonstrated keen
interest in the coming fourth republic politics to do so.
</P>
<P>
"Under these circumstances, I feel obligated at this time to
dissolve the Federal Executive Council with immediate effect to
pave way for the constitution of a new cabinet," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to rules of the transition program, all the
government officials must resign if they want to contest in any
of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Abacha also announced the release of the political detainees
"whose release would constitute no further impediment to the
peace and security of our country."
</P>
<P>
He did not announce the names of those to be released, saying
that this will be left to the appropriate agency.
</P>
<P>
Among those detainees whose releases have been much canvassed
are Chief M.K.O. Abiola, believed to be the winner of the
annulled June 1993 presidential election, General Olusegun
Obasanjo, former head of state jailed for his role in the aborted
1995 coup. 
</P>
