<HEADLINE> Canadians Take Three Golds at World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Canadians claimed three
gold medals Sunday at the World Cup long track speed skating
competiton in Roseville, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Susan Auch, 31, clocked 39.86 seconds to win the women's 500
meters for her first World Cup victory since beating five-time
Olympic champion Bonnie Blair of the United Stated in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Catriona Le May Doan, a medallist at the past two world
championships, grabbed her first World Cup event in the women's
1,000 meters timing one minute, 20.99 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Le May Doan was second in the 500 meters in 39.90.
</P>
<P>
Jeremy Wotherspoon won the men's 500 meters in 36.87 seconds,
the third gold for Canada.
</P>
<P>
Jakko Jan Leeuwangh of the Netherlands captured the gold medal
in the men's 1,000 meters with a time of one minute, 13.80 seconds.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Le May Doan took the 500 and Wotherspoon won the
1,000.
</P>
<P>
The weekends results were the best ever for Canadians at a
World Cup event.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 500, Wotherspoon continued his torrid early-season
pace, setting his second track record this weekend. Yasunori
Miyabe of Japan was second at 36.99 and Grunde Njos of Norway
third in 37.06.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup season continues for the sprinters, next weekend
at the Olympic Oval in Calgary, Canada. 
</P>
