<HEADLINE> Tanzania Set to Re-open Embassy in Kigali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will re-open
its embassy in Kigali early next year, after a three-year
closure, following an improvement in the security situation in
Rwanda, "The East African" newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary in the Tanzanian Ministry of Foreign
Affairs, Elly Mtwango, said last week that with the return of
stability to the central African nation, Tanzania will revive its
mission.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government had evacuated the embassy in 1994 in
the wake of the genocide which saw more than 500,000 members of
the minority Tutsis and some moderate Hutus massacred by their
hardline Hutu countrymen in an orgy of violence that left the
world shocked.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's and other foreign missions based in the Rwandan
capital were not spared the violence, with rampaging mobs raiding
the embassies, looting and destroying property.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's return to Kigali marks a major vote of confidence
in the national reconciliation and reconstruction measures
undertaken by the Rwandan government of President Pasteur
Bizimungu, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
