<HEADLINE> Kenyan Bank's Profits Drop Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Industrial Development
Bank (IDB), a leading bank in Kenya, made a net profit of 46.3
million Shillings last year, down sharply from 91.4 million
Shillings earned in the previous year, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The drop was attributed to a decline in the total income and
an increase in expenses, according to the bank's 1996 annual
report.
</P>
<P>
The bank recorded a deterioration in the collection of
outstanding dues from projects -- from 572.7 million Shillings in
1994/95 to 424 million Shillings in 1995/96 financial year.
Currently around 63 Shillings is equal to one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The bank approved a total of 16 loan investment projects worth
494.4 million Shillings in 1996, compared to 224.5 million
Shillings approved during the previous year. Total disbursement
in 1996 amounted to 302.7 million Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The bank's total expenses increaseed marginally by 2.8 percent
from 555.3 million Shillings in 1994/95 to 571.1 million.
</P>
<P>
The IDB was established in 1973 to assist in the promotion,
establishment, expansion and modernization of medium and
large-scale industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The bank has a medium and long-term lending program, and it
is mandated to facilitate industrial and economic development by
giving out loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
