<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Controversial Labor Bill Set to Pass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- After months of
wrangling, a controversial labor bill looks set to pass South
Africa's parliament, following today's approval by the Labor
Committee of the National Council of Provinces (NCOP).
</P>
<P>
According to the South African Press Association today, the
Basic Conditions of Employment Bill, which cleared the National
Assembly on November 6, will be debated by the NCOP on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill was supported by black-based parties like the African
National Congress, the Pan Africanist Congress and the Inkatha
Freedom Party, but was rejected by traditionally white-dominated
parties, such as the National Party, the Democratic Party and
Freedom Front.
</P>
<P>
The bill, providing for a maximum 45-hour working week and
other privileges for workers like restrictions on extra-time work
and paid maternity leave, was also opposed by certain business
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Experts fear that the bill would increase labor costs and
therefore worsen the already gloomy employment picture in the
country.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 47 percent of black women and 29
percent of black men are jobless.
</P>
<P>
A draft World Bank study blamed the high unemployment rate in
South Africa on high wages paid to black workers, according to a
Business Day newspaper report today.
</P>
<P>
The study, written by World Bank economist Peter Fallon and
Nobel economics laurel Robert Lucas, found that a 10 percent
increase in wages of black workers could lead to a 7.1 percent
decline in employment.
</P>
<P>
Before the bill becomes law early next year, political parties
are expected to push for new amendments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
