<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Assets Gain Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The value of China's
state-owned assets has been growing at an average annual rate of
17.9 percent since 1990, according to a senior industry official.
</P>
<P>
China's state assets, which have gained in value by an average
12.4 percent since 1949 and 14.5 percent since the early 1980s,
were valued at 6.6 trillion yuan by the end of last year, said Zhu
Zhigang, deputy director-general of the State Administration of
State Property.
</P>
<P>
Zhu revealed that the total amount includes nearly 5 trillion
yuan in productive assets, with the remaining being non-productive
assets run by administrative departments and institutions. The
productive assets also include more than 120 billion yuan in
overseas assets.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned economy is in control of the national economic
lifelines, as it is dominant in such sectors as power, coal,
petroleum, metallurgy, chemicals, construction, transportation,
and posts and telecommunications, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that solely state-owned enterprises account for 85
percent of China's total state assets while joint-venture,
cooperative and shareholding companies account for the remaining
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, profit-making enterprises run 74 percent
of the state-owned assets in all enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
