<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebounds Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stocks rebounded sharply today
with the key Nikkei stock price index recovering the 16,000 line for
the first time since November 6 on brisk buying.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section of
the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 1,200.80 points, or 7.96 percent, from
last Friday's close to a session high of 16,283.32.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, gained 80.33 points, or 6.82 percent, to
1,257.85.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 570 million
shares, down from Friday's 623.91 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Traders now see a reversed sentiment in Tokyo, with the Nikkei
average registering the eighth largest point gain in its history.
</P>
<P>
News that Hokkaido Takushoku Bank failed and will transfer its
operations in the Hokkaido area to North Pacific Bank spurred the
buying sentiment because market participants took the announcement as
a sign that other Japanese banks will accelerate liquidation of their
bad loans.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar lost its earlier
gains and drifted in the lower 125 yen level.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was quoted at 125.17-20, down from 126.53-56
yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo and from 125.30-40 yen late Friday in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
