<HEADLINE> Pak PM Denies Contempt of Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif today appeared before the Supreme Court this morning
and denied the allegations that he committed contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
"I have neither committed contempt of court, nor do I intend to
do that," Sharif said in his written reply to the show cause
notice issued by the Supreme Court in a contempt case.
</P>
<P>
Along with 12 others including parliamentarians and government
officials, Sharif appeared before the Supreme Court in a contempt
of court case.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in the history of Pakistan that an
elected prime minister appeared before the apex court.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's statement was read out by the counsel for the prime
minister S.M. Zafar before the five-member Bench of the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
"I hold judiciary, particularly the Supreme Court of Pakistan,
in great esteem and I can never even imagine contempt of court,"
Sharif said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"The country is passing through a very important and critical
phase, and we should devote all our energies to national causes,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"I would do my utmost to deal with national issues with mutual
confidence and cooperation, so that work could go on more
vigorously for the benefit and well-being of the poor of the
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The counsel of the prime minister also submitted today an
application before the Supreme Court, seeking exemption from the
prime minister's personal appearance before it. The Supreme Court
has exempted him from personal appearance at the apex court for
one day on Tuesday due to the visit of U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.  
</P>
</TEXT>
