<HEADLINE> Seoul to Attend Preliminary Meeting of Four-party Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea decided to participate
in the third preliminary meeting of the proposed four-party talks to
discuss permanent peace on the Korean Peninsula, a foreign ministry
spokesman announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
A delegation led by the first assistant to Foreign Minister Song
Yong-shik will be sent to the new round preliminary meeting in New
York on November 21, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Lee Kyu-hyung.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to accept the proposal offered by
Pyongyang last Friday came after an inter-ministrial meeting where
the government officials exchanged the opinions, ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea hopes that the topic agenda and the schedule for the
full four-party talks will be decided in the coming preliminary
talks, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The four-party talks involving South Korea, the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), China and the United States,
is aimed to work out a peace mechanism on the Korean Peninsula
to replace an armistice treaty signed between the U.S.-led "United
Nations" command and DPRK-China side in 1953 to end the three-year
Korean War. 
