<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former S. African President May Face Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president P W Botha may be brought to a legal process since he said he
would not appear before the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC),
local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Botha said in an interview with a Sunday Afrikaans newspaper,
Rapport, that he would rather be taken to court and charged because he
was not prepared to appear before the TRC, a special court to heal the
wounds of the apartheid.
</P>
<P>
TRC chairman, Archbishop Desmond Tutu, Sunday responded with
disappointment with the report and said if that was the case the law
would take its course.
</P>
<P>
Although Tutu didn't elaborate, it is understood that the next step
will be for the commission to decide whether to lay a charge against
Botha in terms of the Promotion of National Unity and Reconciliation
Act.
</P>
<P>
Under the act, anyone who has been subpoenaed does not appear
before the TRC without sufficient cause, he or she faces a fine, up to
two years' jail, or both.
</P>
<P>
Botha was subpoenaed at the end of September to testify in the
mid-October state security council hearing, but refused to appear,
citing health problems.
</P>
<P>
The TRC is expected to hold a second round of hearing in George,
Western Cape, a place close to his retirement home.
</P>
<P>
"I am very sad at the way in which Mr P W Botha has appeared almost
to have thrown down a gauntlet to the TRC in a newspaper interview
published today (Sunday)," Tutu said.
</P>
<P>
The TRC waited since the beginning of the year for answers to
questions which it submitted to Botha in accordance with an agreement
made with him last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said the TRC made special representations to the
government to enable Botha to have necessary legal assistance in order
to provide the necessary answers.
</P>
<P>
The TRC also proposed a special hearing to accommodate Botha after
his representatives indicated that he was not well enough to travel to
Johannesburg last month to attend the hearing on the role of the
former State Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Botha said he would not apologize for the role of his government in
the apartheid era and would not appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
"I will not apologize for the struggle against Marxist
revolutionary attacks which led to the mutilation and death of
innocent civilians," Botha said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would not be threatened and that the TRC could take him
to court if it wanted to.
</P>
<P>
He also attacked the TRC, saying the commission has gradually been
turned into a revenge camp against the Afrikaner.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is simply that the commission does not bring
reconciliation, but is trying to tear the Afrikaner and the South
African nation apart." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
