<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Britain Sign Defense Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Britain
have signed agreements to promote bilateral military operation,
local daily "The Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding and a defense arrangement were
signed in Pretoria last week by South African Defense Minister
Joe Modise and British High Commissioner Maeve Fort.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum provides for increased contact between the
defense sectors of both countries through an exchange of
personnel and students, contact between units assigned for peace
support operations, and ongoing interaction in military
exercises.
</P>
<P>
Britain is one of 10 countries invited to submit proposals to
the South African Defense Department for the supply of new
equipment, primarily new corvettes, submarines, light utility
helicopters, jet fighter/trainers, and battle tanks.
</P>
<P>
The other countries are France, Spain, Italy, Germany, Sweden,
Brazil, Russia, Denmark and Canada. 
</P>
