<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Exporters Complain About High S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan exporters are
demanding that South Africa should open up its market to Kenyan
goods or face a retaliatory lock-out, the weekly East African
reported today.
</P>
<P>
As another giant South African company, Metro Cash and Carry,
starts a wholesale outlet in Nairobi, local exporters are crying
foul over Pretoria's protectionist policies which bar products
from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Although the growth of Kenya's exports to South Africa, mainly
agricultural produce including fruit, tea and coffee, has been
impressive, more products have been shut out by license
restrictions, high tariffs and unfair trade practices, they said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Export Promotion Council (EPC) said that import duties
levied on Kenyan goods by South Africa have been high and import
quotas imposed on South African distributors of Kenyan goods have
discouraged companies intending to export to that country.
</P>
<P>
The EPC said Kenya should either join the Southern African
Development Community in order to enjoy preferential treatment
and avoid restrictions imposed on its products by South Africa,
or impose retaliatory taxes on South African goods.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan textiles attract import duties of as high as 84
percent, making them uncompetitive in South Africa, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also dictates that the country's importers of
Kenyan tea and some other products must buy an equivalent
quantity of domestic products.
</P>
<P>
Among the cases cited by Kenya to illustrate South Africa's
"unfair" trade practices is Pretoria's refusal, until early this
year, to license imports of cut pineapple from Del Monte (Kenya)
Ltd..
</P>
<P>
In contrast, entry into Kenya by South African products such
as wines, chemicals, motor vehicles, beer and textiles has been
easy as they are heavily subsidized, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Director of External Trade at the Kenyan Ministry of Commerce
and Industry L.M. Nderi said last week that the situation had not
improved much despite the launch of talks two years ago between
the two governments to remove barriers to trade.
</P>
<P>
"There is no level playing field in trade between the two
countries as their exports to us are subsidized wile tariff
barriers against us are high," he said.
</P>
<P>
The complaints from Kenya came despite a huge increase in
exports of Kenyan products to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The EPC valued the country's exports to South Africa in 1996
at 2.38 billion Shillings (37.2 million U.S. Dollars), a growth
of 300 percent since 1994.
</P>
<P>
But Kenyan exporters attribute this growth to an expected
natural expansion following the end of apartheid in South Africa,
which opened up the South African market to the world.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, South African exports to Kenya rose by
45 percent, making Kenya its fourth largest export market in
Africa after its traditional trading partners in southern Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Test Million-Round-a-Minute Gun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- An Australian-designed and
built "21st century weapon", a rapid-fire super gun capable of
firing more than one million rounds a minute, is to undergo
evaluation tests by the National Defense Science and Technology
Organization (DSTO), local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The gun, named Metal Storm, is electronically operated and the
first gun in the world to fire without the conventional mechanical
operations, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
It has already undergone successful testing by U.S. defense
officials and is said to have exceeded the criteria set by them,
AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Richard Brabin-Smith, head of DSTO, who signed the
evaluation agreement in Canberra today with inventor Mike O'Dwyer
from Brisbane, said Metal Storm's enormous rate of fire power
would be extremely beneficial in a number of combat situations.
</P>
<P>
It could be a highly successful anti-missile ship defense
system, literally blasting approaching missiles out of the sky
with an impenetrable wall of bullets.
</P>
<P>
O'Dwyer, managing director of Metal Storm Pty Ltd, said the
technology used in Metal Storm could also be used as a
landmine-clearing system. The company is 30 percent owned by
listed company Charter Pacific Corporation Limited in Queensland
state, east Australia.
</P>
<P>
He said because Metal Storm was an electronic firing system it
was possible to have it programmed for use by a single user or
group of users.
</P>
<P>
The technology had attracted worldwide interest, especially
from the Department of Defense of the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Agreements are being negotiated with two U.S. defense
companies. Today's DSTO agreement positions Australia at the
forefront of the use of high technology by the defense industry
and raises the possibility of joint Australian-American
development," O'Dwyer said.
</P>
<P>
O'Dwyer said he was not an engineer, but had a background in
retailing and it had been a long hard job to convince U.S. defense
officials that he had invented a gun everyone had said could not
be successfully designed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
