<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Expected to Net 48 Million Dollars of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is expected to make a
budget surplus of 62 Kwacha (about 48 million U.S. Dollars) this
year, 12.3 million Dollars more than last year.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted a director with the Bank of
Zambia, Feliix Kani, as saying that the first quarter of this
year registered a budget deficit of 19 billion Kwacha (about 14.6
million Dollars) but it was offset by June which accumulated a
surplus of 27 billion Kwacha (about 20.8 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
In September, another surplus of 46 billion Kwacha (about 35.4
million Dollars) was registered.
</P>
<P>
"For this year we envisaged a budget surplus of 62 billion
Kwacha. There is just one month remaining to the close of the
year and we are very close to achieving that," Kani said.
</P>
<P>
The growth target for 1997 is 5.5 percent but so far real
growth is expected to be between three and five percent. The 62
billion Kwacha surplus translates into one percent growth of GDP
already, according to Kani.
</P>
<P>
Although agriculture slackened due to late deliveries of
inputs, there has been a strong performance in non-traditional
exports especially in the tourism sector, construction and
manufacturing, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said under the International Monetary Fund (IMF) program
Zambia implemented, the country is operating a cash budget
and this surplus is a cash-based surplus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
