<HEADLINE> Kenyan Nurses, Laboratory Technicians Seek Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan nurses and laboratory
technicians are demanding an up to 500 present salary increment
within 14 days or they launch a strike, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Kenya Medical Laboratory Scientific
Officers (AKMLSO) southern Nyanza branch said they will not
accept anything short of a 10,000-Shilling (158.7 U.S. Dollars)
risk allowance per month instead of the present 400 Shillings
(6.35 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
"As the backbone of health-care in the country, we are exposed
to infectious diseases such as AIDS/HIV, TB, Cholera and others
and unless we are given a better risk allowance, our next move is
to down our tools," they said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Nurses representatives from Kuria, Suba, Migori, Rachuonyo and
Homa Bay districts in Nyanza Province, where cholera were rampant
a month ago, said they had resolved to jointly participate in the
strike set for November 28.
</P>
<P>
The move was reportedly supported by the AKMLSO headquarters,
which also threatened to take "alternative action" if the
government did not assure them of "adequate remuneration within
21 days."
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Ministry of Health, the association
petitioned the government to implement pay rise recommendations
it gave to a government-appointed committee in charge of
reviewing civil servants salaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
