<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Seeks to Expand Trade Links with Arabs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Israelis are active in
approaching Arab businessmen at an on-going regional economic
conference here which is facing a widespread Arab boycott
against Israel's role in bogging down the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation, led by Minister of Industry and Trade
Natan Sharansky, has seen the possibility of expanding the
Israeli-Arab business dealings.
</P>
<P>
The delegation has been talking to "enough Arab businessmen"
attending the three-day fourth Middle East and North Africa
economic conference which was opened Sunday, a delegation member
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Half of the 68-member delegation are businessmen coming from
various sectors ranging from high-tech to equities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky told reporters here today that some Arab countries
have expressed their interest in an Israeli-Jordanian joint
venture deal signed here Sunday to establish an industrial zone
in Irbid in northern Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Irbid Qualifying Industrial Zone will cover an area of 200
hectares. Products made in the zone can enter the U.S. market with
a duty-free entry. But this benefit is available to Egypt, Israel
and Jordan only.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky did not rule out the possibility for other Arab
countries to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the few Arab countries doing business with
Israel in a public way, while many Arab countries have been
imposing a collective economic block against Israel for decades
in protest against Israeli occupation of Arab land.
</P>
<P>
But still, many Israeli products bearing non-Israeli labels
can be seen in Arab markets like Syria and Iran. "The boycott
(of the conference) is only in political words, but not in
business dealings," an Israeli analyst made the comment to
Xinhua, asking her name not to be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Sharansky said that Jordan and Israel will start
to discuss the establishment of a bilateral free trade zone next
month.
</P>
<P>
Another major project under discussion during the conference
is Israel's purchase of gas, with any one of Egypt, Qatar or
Russia, the minister said. This project used to be considered
canceled due to the boycott.
</P>
<P>
Arab leading countries like Egypt, Saudi Arabia and the United
Arab Emirates are joining the political boycott camp, but the
business representation is much wider.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab countries said holding Arab-Israeli economic
conference like the Doha will undermine the Arab economic block
against Israel and thus deprive Arabs of bargaining chips in
peace negotiations and reward Israel's hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
Israelis' campaign to seek expansion of business links with
Arabs is of more significance in political rather than economic
terms, the Israeli analyst said, adding "for Israel, the Doha
conference is ideal for doing a public relation job." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
