<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
received a burst of life today, strengthening against its U.S.
counterpart, as regional equity markets lifted their game.
</P>
<P>
The local unit settled at 70.15 U.S. cents, the first time it
had closed above the 70.00 U.S. cent level in more than a week.
</P>
<P>
It was substantially higher than the 69.90 U.S. cent close late
Friday but off its high for today's session of 70.50 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Societe Generale chief economist Glenn Maguire said the
economic data last week revealed the extent to which the
Australian currency has become decoupled from the domestic
economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"This circumstance is somewhat frustrating for Australian
dollar bulls, however, it does raise the possibility that when
market attention returns to the Australian fundamentals, there
could be quite a strong bounce in the Australian dollar," Maguire
said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 87.85 yen from 87.84 previously,
and at 1.2174 marks, from 1.2048 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
