<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Marginally Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed marginally higher in a day dominated by the listing of the
country's newest and biggest company, Telstra Corp.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 8.6 points higher at 2487.7 on
strong turnover resulting from trading in the telecommunications
giant.
</P>
<P>
Telstra Corp's installment receipts closed at 2.67 Australian
dollars, representing a 72 Australian cent premium for retail
investors and a 67 cent premium on the issue price.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said there was a mixed attitude in the market, with the
shares of profit takers quickly snapped by buyers who saw more
value in the stock.
</P>
<P>
Telstra lists in the United States tonight.
</P>
<P>
Telstra trade represented more than half the value of today's
sharemarket trade here, at 296.2 million shares traded at a value
of 555.7 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, it is yet to be included in calculating the all
ordinaries index.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was 532.38 million shares at a
value of 1.03 billion U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises
by 554 to 482.
</P>
<P>
Aside from Telstra, 480.4 million U.S. dollars of shares were
traded.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 38.4 points to 4215.0.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, ANZ and Westpac were the main improvers,
increasing 19 cents to 10.28 Australian dollars and 29 cents to
9.00 Australian dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Bank increased ten cents to 11.80 Australian dollars
after announcing its net profit for the six months to September 30
rose 39.7 percent to 45.09 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank increased 11.6 cents to 17.166 Australian
dollars and National Australia Bank rose four cents to 20.50
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 17.6 points to 1114.9 with some of
the major stocks sold down significantly.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP fell 22 cents to 13.88 Australian dollars
while mining giant WMC lost most of its recent recovery, falling
27 cents to 5.13 Australian dollars. Rio Tinto dropped 20 cents to
16.51 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks also took a tumble, with the index down almost four
percent, or 38.8 points, at 961.0. 
</P>
</TEXT>
