<HEADLINE> Sharif Exempted from Personal Appearance at Apex Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif was exempted here today by the Supreme Court from
personal appearance at the apex court.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court adjourned till Tuesday the hearing of
contempt case against Prime Minister Sharif, Law Minister Khalid
Anwar and others.
</P>
<P>
The counsel of the prime minister, Mohammad Zafar, today
submitted an application before the court, seeking exemption from
personal appearance of the prime minister before it.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice Syed Sajjad Ali Shah, who presided over the
five-member bench, hearing the case, said the decision on the
application would be made tomorrow. However, he allowed the
exemption for one day on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Court refused exemption to other respondents in the case,
including Law Minister Khalid Anwar.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court headed by Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah today
took up the contempt of court petitions against Prime Minister
Sharif and seven members of the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
And for the first time in the history of Pakistan, a prime
minister has been summoned, through a judicial order in contempt
of court proceedings by appearing in the court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
