<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Should Not Be Left out of ASEM: Mahathir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar, as it is now a
member of ASEAN, should not be excluded from the Asia-Europe
Meeting (ASEM) in London next year, Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said today.
</P>
<P>
Keeping Myanmar out would not help bring about the changes that
were expected of Yangon, Mahathir said at a joint news conference
with French President Jacques Chirac after their talks in
Langkawi, a resort island in Northern Malaysia, where Chirac
arrived yesterday for an overnight working visit.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN views that there should be direct contact with the
people of Myanmar because in that way, it can help influence them
in accepting the kind of norms the world seems to be insisting
on," he was quoted by the Malaysian national news agency Bernama
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir gave his view while replying to a French journalist
who wanted to know his stand on Myanmar's exclusion from the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
To lay conditions on Myanmar is not conducive to boosting
dialogue between regional partners, Mahathir said, adding "We
should determine who represents ASEAN or Southeast Asian
countries (for ASEM). It is for us to decide."
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, together with Laos was admitted into ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) last July.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN also groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
