<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Manufacturing Output Up in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's output of
manufactured products increased by 13.4 percent in September,
marking the fourth consecutive rise this year, the Economic
Development Board (EDB) said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The increase was broad-based, with high growth in the
electronics, chemicals, machinery and transport equipment
industries," the EDB observed.
</P>
<P>
The electronics industry grew by 16.3 percent year-on-year in
September, it said, adding that the increase was the industry's
highest and fourth consecutive growth this year.
</P>
<P>
All major segments expanded except for consumer electronics, as
there was higher demand for higher value-added chips and printed
circuit boards assembled. Output growth of disk drive and
telecommunication equipment was still healthy albeit at a slower
rate of growth, the EDB said.
</P>
<P>
The chemicals industries expanded by 15.6 percent in September,
while cumulative output for the first nine months of 1997 was 17.1
percent. The petrochemical industry maintained its high growth in
September, with output of petrochemical products increasing by
125.1 percent, contributed mainly by the additional capacities in
the industry.
</P>
<P>
The output of the petroleum industry increased by 12 percent,
while the cumulative output for the first nine months of the year
grew by only 0.3 percent compared to the same period in 1996 as
output was relatively low in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
The output of machinery increased by 26.4 percent in September
because of higher output of lifting machinery, machine tools and
conversion work done on an oil rig.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the output of pharmaceuticals declined by 39.7
percent in September. But the cumulative output for the first nine
months increased by 4.1 percent compared to the same period of
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
