<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Polish Presidents Hold Talks in Beijing   (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
expressed the hope here today that his country and Poland would
make joint efforts to establish bilateral ties with a perspective
towards the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with visiting Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski, Jiang said that the visit of his Polish counterpart
will help to further the traditional friendship between people of
the two countries, and enhance bilateral ties to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski agreed with Jiang, saying the visit will make a
positive contribution to friendship and cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the 90-minute talk, the two leaders exchanged views on
furthering the friendly ties and international issues with common
concern.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that, although great changes had taken place in the
world as well as in the two countries over recent years, the
Sino-Polish bilateral ties continued their stable development and
will stand the test of time. The two countries have maintained
high-level frequent contacts, expanded exchanges and cooperation
in fields of economics, science and technology, culture and
education, as well as understand and support each other on many
international issues, Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang attributed the following factors as reasons why
bilateral ties could develop so smoothly:
</P>
<P>
-- Advancing bilateral friendly cooperation is the common wish
of the people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
-- There are extensive common interests rather than conflict of
fundamental interests between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
-- Both countries can handle bilateral ties by disregarding
the differences in their social systems, ideology and values.
</P>
<P>
-- China and Poland can strictly follow the principles of mutual
respect, equality and mutual non-interference into each other's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon two-way trade, Jiang said China regards economic
cooperation with Poland as an important component part of
bilateral ties, and Poland is China's major trade partner in
eastern Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Polish Presidents Hold Talks in Beijing   (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Recent years have shown constant growth in two-way trade and
the steady increase of trade volume, Jiang said, adding that the
two sides also tried to maintain a balanced trade by strengthening
the exchanges of companies and business communities of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes Polish businesses to enter the Chinese market,
participating in large projects such as the Three Gorges project,
he said, adding that the two countries should encourage and
support their businesses and regions with strength and good
reputations to increase contacts and understanding, and explore
various kinds of economic and technological cooperation on
different levels and in various ways.
</P>
<P>
China will also spur its businesses to compete in the Polish
market, Jiang noted.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski said Poland pays great attention to its economic
cooperation with China, and that there is potential in this
regard. The Polish entrepreneurs accompanying him on the tour said
they hoped for in-depth discussions with their Chinese
counterparts, Kwasniewski said.
</P>
<P>
Poland also hopes to expand its exchanges and cooperation with
China in the fields of culture, sports, science and technology, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang gave a briefing on his recent visit to the United States,
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's China trip, and China's foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his appreciations to the Polish president and the
Polish government's adherence to the "one China" policy. He also
said that China understands Poland's policy of giving priority to
pursuing ties with European countries.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski invited Jiang to visit Poland at his convenience,
and Jiang accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
After the talk, the two heads of state signed a joint
communique, and officials from the two sides also signed an
agreement of cooperation on the quarantine of animals and animal
hygiene, as well as an implementation plan for bilateral cultural
and scientific cooperation from 1998 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talk, President Jiang presided at a ceremony in
honor of President Kwasniewski.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the two countries also reached four agreements on
bilateral economic cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
