<HEADLINE> Indian Airport Operators to Strike for Higher wages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Operators of air traffic
controllers (ATC) in India on Sunday said they will disrupt flight
movement at all airports from next week by stopping work for one
hour each time for four times a day to press for higher wages.
</P>
<P>
Today's local press reports quoted Brijendra Shekhar, general
secretary of the ATC Guild, said that complete stoppage of work
was also possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that the work stoppage will begin on November 21.
</P>
<P>
The ATC Guild, which demands a wage hike and other benefits for
ATC operators, has in the past two weeks been on a slow agitation
disrupting and delaying flights at major Indian airports such as
Delhi, Bangalore, Bombay, Calcutta and Chennai (Madras).
</P>
<P>
But the disruption has not been continuous and shifted from one
airport to another without causing chaos in all airports.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to intensify the agitation," said R. K. Singh,
president of the ATC Guild, indicating that the path of "direct
action" was the only option for mounting pressure on the airport
authority of India.
</P>
<P>
An agitation move by ATC operators half a year ago led to the
suspension of all domestic and international flights over India,
the ripples of which was felt all over the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
</TEXT>
