<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Peasants Love Local Opera (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The curtain rose with two
thousand eyes fixed on the simply built plank stage. With a rapid
beating of gongs and drums, a young boy in traditional costume
performed a series of somersaults from the left to the right of
the stage followed by thunderous applause in this remote village.
</P>
<P>
A theatrical troupe was performing a type of Chinese local
opera known as Manhan opera in Xingshuxi, a village in northern
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The story told about a warrior fighting to the death on a
battlefield. When the warrior bid farewell to his wife before
going to the front, a woman under the stage with her baby sleeping
in her arms got misty-eyed.
</P>
<P>
The three-hour performance attracted all the villagers, who
rallied around the stage long before the performance. They were
dressed in their best clothes usually worn during festivals.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jinyu, a rural teacher, walked 15 kilometers from a nearby
village to enjoy the play.
</P>
<P>
Jiao Bingquan, 63, said they can only watch such a play once or
twice a year.
</P>
<P>
A young man, Bian Liang, pointing at a girl beside him, said
they met last time when they went to the play one year ago and
fell in love with each other.
</P>
<P>
"It's a good chance to meet friends while watching opera," Bian
said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese peasants have a long history of watching local
operas. Many of the opera's subjects are historic stories. Old men
often told the ancient stories to their children and
grandchildren. Many stories have been performed hundreds of years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Peasants Love Local Operas (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In recent years, modern media such as television have entered
China's rural areas, affecting the development of traditional
local operas, some of which have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
However, some new types of dramas close to the farmer's life
have been developed. More than 300 types of local operas have been
developed in China, with 80 new types such as the Manhan Opera.
</P>
<P>
Manhan Opera, popular in the western region of Inner Mongolia,
is performed mainly by two persons. The unique style of opera has
assimilated the traditional Mongolian songs and dances.
</P>
<P>
Compared with well-known Chinese operas such as the Peking
Opera, Manhan Opera and many other local operas are not fully
developed as an artistic form. The costumes, properties and the
melody of the operas are much simpler.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Chinese farmers showed great interest in local
operas, which usually tell stories about the marriage, family
problems and the work of Chinese farmers. The performers, many of
whom are farmers, can be either professionals or amateurs.
</P>
<P>
Guan Yiquan, head of the Manhan troupe founded in 1986, said
his group has performed in China's countryside more than 100 times
last year, with the audience surpassing 100,000.
</P>
<P>
Guan added that his troupe has been awarded more than 50
national prizes, including the Plum Blossom Prize, China's most
prestigious prize in theatrical circles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
