<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Takes Measures to Help Retarded: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina has said her government is considering with due
importance the setting up of a national institute for the mentally
retarded.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made this statement while inaugurating the
week-long 13th Asian Conference on Mental Retardation in Dhaka
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Rights of persons with mental retardation: role of government
and UN agencies in Asia," is the theme of the conference, being
held for the first time in the country with the representation of
400 mentally disabled persons, including 150 from different Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
The government is pledge-bound to ensure proper upbringing of
the disabled through care, education and training, the independent
United News of Bangladesh (UNB) quoted the prime minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"The government will do its utmost for the welfare of the
mentally retarded persons of the country," she stated.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister called upon all including the UN agencies
working in the country to assist in resolving the acute problem.
</P>
<P>
According to the organizers of the conference, Bangladesh has
1.2 million mentally retarded persons, of which only 3,500 are
getting institutional support.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, "the mentally retarded persons are not
a burden of the society. They can also contribute a lot in the
development activities if they are provided with necessary
treatment, nursing, education and training."
</P>
<P>
The government is planning to set up a national institute for
the mentally retarded, the prime minister said, adding that ten
percent job quota in government service has been reserved for the
disabled including the mentally retarded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
