<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Eyes U.N. Procurement Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is urging
local firms to pay more attention to the United Nations market,
saying the market is worth some 4 billion U.S. dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will see more opportunities as the U.N. has assigned
its procurement agencies to increase its purchasing ratio from
developing countries, said Sanit Vorapanya, director-general of
the Export Promotion Department of the Thai Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Medicine and medical supplies, food, communication equipment,
vehicles, construction equipment, garments, textiles and kitchen
equipment are the goods which the U.N. is interested in, today's
local press reports quoted Sanit as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most Thai businessmen have a little knowledge on how to sell
goods to the U.N. and they should take the opportunity to learn
the procedures and increase their sales to the U.N. when its teams
visit Thailand, Sanit said.
</P>
<P>
Asda Jayanama, a Thai representative to the U.N. said that
companies wanting to do business with the U.N. should register
with one of the U.N. agencies and tender their procurement
methods.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only seven Thai companies have registered with U.N.
agencies, Asda said.
</P>
<P>
Toshiyki Niwa, U.N. assistant secretary-general, said during a
recent visit to Thailand that U.N. purchases depend on quality,
delivery, after-sales services and pricing.
</P>
<P>
He said in his opinion Thai goods generally meet these
standards, but he expressed the hope that Thai businessmen would
offer low prices.
</P>
<P>
Peter Adler, a U.N. procurement officer, said last year 45
percent of the U.N. total purchase was from developing countries
and the U.N. bought more from Thailand than from Indonesia,
Malaysia and Singapore together.
</P>
<P>
Adler said that most goods the U.N. purchased were food and
consumer products and that the U.N. is planning to increase
purchases of manufactured goods like electronic products in the
future.
</P>
<P>
He foresaw that U.N. purchases from Thailand will rise in the
future due to more attractive price offers from Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
