<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French President Supports Malaysia to Regulate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques
Chirac today gave full support to Malaysia's proposal for
regulations to be introduced for currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Chirac agreed there should be regulations in currency trading
so that there would not be an anarchy, Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said today after holding talks with Chirac in
Langkawi, a resort island in Northern Malaysia, where Chirac
arrived yesterday for an overnight working visit.
</P>
<P>
"Chirac is not saying that we should restrict but there should
not be an anarchy, this is being able to raise 20 times your
capital through leverage. That's something that needs to be
investigated by the IMF (International Monetary Fund)," Mahathir
was quoted by reports reaching here as telling local reporters
there.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, Chirac informed Mahathir that he
(Chirac) had spoken to IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus over
the telephone last night.
</P>
<P>
The French president also agreed that the Group of 15 (G-15)
developing countries should be represented when the Group of Seven
(G-7) industrialized countries discuss the currency issue.
</P>
<P>
Chirac believed that the G-15 and G-7 must have a closer
relation because whatever the G-7 decided had an implication on
the G15, Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that Chirac was in favor of having a G-15
representative in the G-7 and had asked Malaysia to initiate
efforts towards that.
</P>
<P>
On the United States probe into a gas deal in Iran involving
Malaysian and French petroleum companies, Mahathir said France's
stand was similar to Malaysia's, that is, no country should decide
for another.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said: "Even France is against sanctions like us. These
are not the World Trade Organization's rules but merely one
country's decision."
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader said Chirac, in fact, wanted further
cooperation with Malaysia's oil company Petronas in other areas
and not just confined to Iran.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Secretary of State for Energy, Sanctions and
Commodities William Ramsay is due to arrive here tomorrow to probe
the 2 billion joint venture between Petronas, France's Total SA
and Russia's Gazprom in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is in Malaysia after attending a gathering of
French-speaking countries in Hanoi, Vietnam. His visit is the
first by a French head of state to Malaysia. He leaves later
today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
