<HEADLINE> Guangxi to Build Five Economic Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, a multi-ethnic area in south China, is preparing to build
five economic zones, each with its own unique features.
</P>
<P>
An economic zone catering to port transport, marine and
high-tech development will be built on the coastal area in
southern Guangxi, Cao Bochun, secretary of the Autonomous Regional
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), announced at a
regional meeting held here recently.
</P>
<P>
The central part of Guangxi will build an economic zone
centering around industrial production.
</P>
<P>
The zone in the region's northern part will emphasize tourism,
agriculture and industry.
</P>
<P>
In the eastern part, rural industry and export-oriented economy
will be featured.
</P>
<P>
Western Guangxi will pay special attention to cultivation and
mining.
</P>
<P>
Formation of a diversified economy is an inevitable trend in
accelerating the regional economy, Cao said.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi is endowed with many superior qualities compared with
other parts of China. It is a communications link between southern
and southwestern China and is rich in sub-tropical and undergrand
resources.
</P>
<P>
So far, governments in the autonomous region have worked out
measures to develop key industries and enhance regional
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Beihai, a city on the northern coast, is speeding up the third
phase of its port construction and the building of an
expressway. Fangcheng port plans to raise its annual handling
capacity above 12 million tons. The city of Nanning, the
autonomous region's capital, is boosting border trade with Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Liuzhou Prefecture in central Guangxi will readjust assets of
state-owned enterprises and build a multi-lateral investment
system.
</P>
<P>
Baise Prefecture in the west will accelerate economic growth
along the Nanning-Kunming Railway and shift its emphasis to the
processing industry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yulin and Wuzhou, cities in the eastern part, will
introduce funds, technology and expertise, as well as qualified
personnel to promote development at foreign-funded and
township-run firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
