<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Survey Shallow Water of Coastal Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Geological Survey of
Bangladesh (GSB) in collaboration with the German Geological
Survey (GGS) has undertaken geological survey of the shallow water
area of the country for long term development of the coastal zone,
the GSB sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
To be run over twenty days with financial support from the
German Ministry of Science, Technology and Education, the survey
will determine the flux of sand and mud from the delta into the
sea, especially into the shallow submarine areas of the shelf,
study cyclones, investigate the record of cyclones in the deposits
of the shelf and determine the subsidence of the shelf and coastal
area since 20,000 years ago, according to GSB's Deputy Director
General Abdullah Monwar.
</P>
<P>
A German research vessel, "Sonne", arrived in the harbor of
Chittagong Saturday for taking part in the geological survey, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sand and mud, which have been deposited in the shallow
submarine areas, especially in water depths from 20 to 80 meters,
have bypassed the coastal zone and are therefore not supporting
the growth of coastal islands, the sources noted, adding that the
sand and mud bypassing the shelf into the deep by of Bengal (Bay)
are completely lost for any land accretion.
</P>
<P>
The survey project is focused on mapping the submarine
depositional areas and on measuring how much material is dumped in
these areas, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
It will also compile a long term record for the cyclones
affecting the coast of Bangladesh providing data to analyze trends
in the frequency of cyclones and how they are related to long term
climatic chances of El Nino events, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Five scientists from various institutions and Bangladesh Navy
are participating in the survey cruise and later in the evaluation
of the data.
</P>
<P>
The results of the survey and of the previous similar pilot
project in 1994, the sources said, will be discussed during a
seminar in 1998 involving all institutions which study the coastal
zone of Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
