<HEADLINE> Malaysia, China Sign New MOU on Civil Aviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and the People's
Republic of China signed here today a Memorandum of Understanding
(MOU) providing for an enhanced air services arrangement between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The new MOU provides among others a multiple airline
designation clause allowing either country to designate any number
of airlines to operate services between Malaysia and China
beginning in 1998 until 2005.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed in the MOU to increase passenger frequencies
on a phased basis during the period and to increase cargo services
for the designated airlines of both countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the MOU, signed by Malaysian Transport Minister
Ling Liong Sik and Chinese Minister of General Administration of
Civil Aviation Chen Guangyi on behalf of their respective
governments, landing sites in Malaysia for airlines of China will
increase from the present two -- Kuala Lumpur and Pulau Pinang --
to three with the third one to be chosen while landing sites in
China for airlines of Malaysia will increase from the present
three -- Beijing, Guangzhou and Shanghai -- to six with the other
three -- Xiamen, Kunming and Shenzhen -- chosen already.
</P>
<P>
Both Ling and Chen told reporters after the signing that the
MOU underscores the common will and desire of the two countries to
further strengthen bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
They said the MOU heralds a new chapter in the aviation
relationship and will create new opportunities for the further
development of air links and airline cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They believed that with the new MOU, exchanges between the
peoples, trade and tourism would be further promoted to bring
about greater economic benefits to both sides.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and China established aviation relationship in 1988
when the two countries signed their air services agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister arrived here last night for a three-day
visit to Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
