<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Thapa Elected Chairman of RPP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Surya Bahadur
Thapa of Nepal was again elected Chairman of the National
Democratic Party (RPP) on Sunday in the absence of his arch rival
former Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand, Radio Nepal reported
today.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the second general convention of the RPP in
Birgunj, about 120 km southwest of Kathmandu, Thapa garnered a
majority of 818 votes, while his rival Rajeshwor Devkota, the
party's former co-chairman, received only 391 votes.
</P>
<P>
The convention also amended the party's statute by establishing
a 41-member executive committee headed by the party chairman,
putting an end to the tradition of collective leadership.
</P>
<P>
Lokendra Bahadur Chand, the RPP's former parliamentary party
leader, boycotted the convention, alleging that Thapa had
dissolved the party's elected organizations in at least 10
districts and packed them with his own supporters.
</P>
<P>
Chand was voted out of power in early October by the Nepali
Congress (NC) with a no-confidence motion after Thapa sided with
the NC.
</P>
<P>
The RPP (Thapa) and the RPP (Chand) merged in early 1992, but
they have never stopped in-fighting.
</P>
<P>
The NC and the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML), the two main parties in parliament,
have taken advantage of the RPP's division for a new political
equation in the past years, making the RPP, the third largest
party in parliament, a weight in the political balance of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the NC will join the RPP-led
coalition government after the RPP convention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
