<HEADLINE> Indian Gems Are Not Radioactive: Scientist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- An Indian scientist, who has
done pioneering work on irradiation of gemstones, refuted the
charge by western countries that gems exported from India were
radioactive, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
Nataraja Sarma, formerly with India's Bhabha Atomic Research
Center (BARC), said there was "no truth in such wild allegations
and nothing is done in this country that resulted in gemstones
becoming radioactive."
</P>
<P>
He said that before his retirement from BARC, he had worked to
produce "rare and expensive black diamond" through "neutron
irradiation" process on an experimental basis but the project was
subsequently shot down by the BARC top brass.
</P>
<P>
Under the "neutron irradiation" process, ordinary diamond is
put in a nuclear reactor to achieve black diamond, a rare and
precious commodity.
</P>
<P>
Diamond is a form of carbon, there is no way it could turn
radioactive after irradiation, he said.
</P>
<P>
But it has been found in similar research in western countries
that when impure diamond is used for irradiation, the metallic
impurities in diamond get irradiated and hence care needs to be
taken that there is no impurity in the diamond that is being
irradiated, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are two other methods through which other precious and
semi-precious gemstones are irradiated for getting higher value
gemstones, Sarma said, but adding that both of them do not result
in irradiated gemstones becoming radioactive.
</P>
<P>
Gemstones are a major item of India's export basket.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0171 </DOCNO>
