<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Paddy Production to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's paddy production
this year is expected to drop by 3.85 percent to 49.13 million
tons from 51.10 million tons last year, the Central Bureau of
Statistics (BPS) predicts.
</P>
<P>
According to a BPS estimate released Sunday, the expected
decline of paddy production is mainly due to the shrinking areas
of paddy farmland, which is estimated at 11.04 million hectares
this year, down by 4.65 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
Sumatra Island is likely to record a 7.17 percent fall in paddy
output, followed by Sulawesi and Kalimantan with decreases of 7.14
percent and 5.81 percent respectively, it said.
</P>
<P>
The BPS also said the country's total output of corn is
expected to decline by 1.34 percent to 9.18 million tons this
year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Minister of Agriculture Sjarifudin Baharsjah said
Indonesia's production of unhusked rice would drop by 4 percent in
1997 compared with 1996 because of a prolonged dry season.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, formerly the biggest rice importer in the world,
became self-sufficient in rice supply in 1984. However, it began
to import rice again in 1991 due to the shrinking paddy areas and
bad weather conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
