<HEADLINE> Singapore Revises Upwards 1997 GDP Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government has
revised its 1997 gross domestic product (GDP) forecast a bit
higher from the original 6-7 percent to around 7 percent, the
Ministry of Trade and Industry (MTI) said today.
</P>
<P>
In an economic survey for the third quarter of 1997, the
ministry said the country's economy grew by a healthy 7.5 percent
in the first three quarters of this year, as it continued to pick
up in the third quarter after bottoming out in the second half of
last year.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook for the rest of the year remains healthy, with
some moderation in growth in 1998," it said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry noted that the prospects for the external
environment are mixed and the regional economies are expected to
slow down as a result of the recent financial crisis. However,
healthy growth in industrial economies, except for Japan, and the
sustained global electronics recovery would underpin external
demand over the rest of 1997 and 1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
Domestically, the ministry said, overall economic growth in
1997 "is expected to be healthy given the strong momentum in the
first nine months."
</P>
<P>
"Taking all these factors into consideration, the MTI is
revising its 1997 GDP forecast from 6-7 percent to around 7
percent. Going into 1998, some moderation of growth can be
expected as regional growth slows down further. The MTI's
preliminary 1998 GDP forecast is 5-7 percent," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
