<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Construction Companies Thrive Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korean construction
companies are thriving overseas, enjoying the greatest boom since
the late 1970s when demand was record high in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Statistics of the Korean International Contractors Association
(KICA) show that by November 16 domestic builders received orders
amounting to 10.73 billion U.S. dollars from abroad, just 50
million dollars less than the 10.78 billion dollars of the entire
1996.
</P>
<P>
With that in mind, KICA officials said, this year's total
volume of orders is predicted to approach 16 billion dollars,
surely exceeding the initially-set target of 12 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Given that some projected overseas contracts are virtually in
the bag, the possibility is running high that a new record in
volume of overseas construction orders might be established this
year, they said.
</P>
<P>
The previous record was 13.7 billion dollars set in 1981,
mainly boosted by high demand in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The officials attributed this year's good performance to South
Korean companies' continued efforts to change business patterns
and expand markets through advancing to markets that had
traditionally been paid less attention to.
</P>
<P>
South Korean companies, instead of resorting to past practices
of basic participation in bids through invitation by foreign
governments or firms placing orders, have increasingly put more
energy into BOT (build, operate, transfer) projects in developing
countries facing lack of capital, and other similar type of
projects.
</P>
<P>
Topping the list of companies, Hyundai Engineering &AMP;
Construction received the largest amount of orders worth 3.49
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Next came Daewoo Corp. with 2.61 billion dollars, followed by
Samsung Corp. with 820 million dollars and Ssangyong Engineering &AMP;
Construction Co. with 720 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overseas construction orders, which had been decreasing since
the early 1980s to 2.8 billion dollars in 1992, have been on the
rapid rise in recent years since 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to KICA, the total was 5.1 billion dollars in 1993,
7.4 billion dollars in 1994, 8.5 billion dollars in 1995 and 10.78
billion dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy Grows 10.1 Pct in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's economy
continued to pick up in the third quarter of this year, expanding
by a robust 10.1 percent, further up from 8.2 percent in the
second quarter, the Ministry of Trade and Industry (MTI) said
today.
</P>
<P>
"The favorable performance was characterized by faster growth
in all sectors," the ministry said in an economic survey.
</P>
<P>
"The strong growth indicates that the real economy was not
significantly affected by the regional financial turmoil, though
there was some impact on the volume of re-exports and visitor
arrivals from selected regional economies," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore economy has been cushioned by two main factors,
the ministry explained. First, a large part of Singapore's
regional trade consists of intra-firm movement of parts,
components and final products by Multi-National Corporations
(MNCs). As final demand from the United States and the European
Union remained strong, Singapore's trade was not seriously
affected by the regional currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, it said, a healthy recovery in global electronics
demand supported manufacturing growth, with its favorable spin-off
effects on trade and hub services.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry noted that there was also a low base
effect, as the economy expanded by only 3.3 percent in the
corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, manufacturing output continued to
recover in the third quarter of this year, growing by a robust 9.5
percent, substantially stronger than the 3.5 percent a quarter
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector expanded by 13 percent, due to higher
public and private-sector residential activity and public civil
engineering works, helped by dry weather during the three-month
period.
</P>
<P>
The commerce sector increased by 8.6 percent in the third
quarter, up from the eight percent level a quarter earlier. Growth
was largely supported by higher retail activity on account of the
Great Singapore Sale and Singapore Food Festival.
</P>
<P>
In financial services, the ministry said, the regional currency
crisis and uncertainty over the merging of the local and foreign
tranches of some listed companies boosted stock market turnover,
while foreign exchange activity moderated somewhat in the third
quarter as traders remained cautious.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the financial and business services sector rose by 12
percent in the third quarter, largely unchanged from the 11
percent growth a quarter earlier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
