<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC to be urged to push business cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) economies will urge APEC
leaders to focus on business cooperation in the region,
particularly cross-border trade and investment, a leading Thai
business representative said.
</P>
<P>
The APEC Business Advisory Council (ABAC) will raise issues
concerned at a meeting between its representatives and APEC
ministers in Vancouver, Canada on November 23, one day before an
APEC leadership's informal conference begins in the same city,
said Vachara Phanchet, executive director of the Thai Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The ABAC, which comprises private sector representatives from
APEC members, will urge APEC leaders to relax visa regulations
concerning business trips throughout the region, including the
extension of visa for businessmen, today's local press reports
quoted Vachara as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ABAC will also urge the 18 APEC members to establish a
customs harmonization system regionwide and a common standard for
doing business, said Vachara, who will attend the ABAC meeting
together with other Thai private sector representatives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ABAC will seek APEC ministers' support to speed
up the process of liberalization in investment to allow more
involvement of the private sector in the area, particularly in
infrastructure investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ABAC will push for an APEC information and
education initiative to allow small- and medium-sized enterprises
to get up-to-date information on the world market, Vachara said.
</P>
<P>
He said that some 80 percent of Thailand's manufacturing
enterprises are small or medium-sized and the plan will help
Thailand to strengthen its manufacturing sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
