<HEADLINE> Heavy Drinking, Binge Drinking Surveyed in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Recent studies indicate a
substantial decline in alcoholism among white men in the United
States while binge drinking among college students is still a
serious problem.
</P>
<P>
A University of California at Berkeley study released earlier
this week has found that the portion of white men aging between 18
and 29 who report drinking heavily has dropped by half, from 32
percent down to 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
That was the result of a nationwide survey covering more than
6,000 American men and women who were white, black and Latino. It
is said to be the first large-scale study that compares drinking
rates among different ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The decline did not include young black and Latino men. The
study found that 18 percent of young black and 17 percent of
Latino men were frequent heavy drinkers.
</P>
<P>
"Heavy drinking" is defined as taking five or more drinks in
one sitting at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
Heavy drinking among white men used to peak in their 20s, 30s
and then decline. The study suggests that young, white American
men have broken a pattern of heavy drinking that had persisted in
a significant portion of that population for a generation.
</P>
<P>
Although rates of heavy drinking have declined among young
white men, the study found that the level of "alcohol-related
problems" remains the same. The problems include belligerence,
accidents and problems with police, spouse or the workplace.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a recent study by the Harvard School of Public
Health found that binge drinking on college campuses has been on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
With data collected from a national sample of nearly 17,600
students at 140 four-year colleges and universities, the Harvard
survey on college drinking is said to provide a complete portrait
of student drinking behavior.
</P>
<P>
"Binge drinking" for men is defined as having five or more
drinks in a row, and for women as having four or more drinks in a
row.
</P>
<P>
The study shows 44 percent of U.S. college students engage in
binge drinking, and at almost one-third of the colleges more than
half of the students were binge drinkers.
</P>
<P>
The overall rate among men is 50 percent and among women, 39
percent. About half the binge drinkers, or about one in five
students overall, were frequent binge drinkers.
</P>
<P>
"The current level of binge drinking by U.S. college students
is a serious problem," the study concluded. The problem not only
interferes with the mission of higher education, but also carries
with it serious risks of disease, injury and death, it said.
</P>
<P>
The study group urged school administration to consider such
measures as establishing a policy of "zero tolerance" for
alcohol-related violence, regulating the conditions of alcohol use
on campus, and eliminating sponsorship of events by the alcohol
industry and other on-campus marketing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
