<HEADLINE> Thai Shrimp Exports Drop on Higher EU Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Shrimp exports, one of
Thailand's top foreign exchange earners, have declined since the
European Union (EU) imposed higher tariffs under its new general
system of preference (GSP) on January 1, according to an industry
survey available today.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's shrimp exports in the first seven months of this
year dropped by 8 percent to 76,413 tons compared with 83,122 tons
in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Shrimp exports to the EU registered the biggest drop of 19
percent from 8,786 tons to 7,144 tons, a result of higher import
duty on Thai shrimp products.
</P>
<P>
Before January 1, Thai products were levied by a 4.5 percent
import duty, the same rate applied to shrimp products from
Malaysia, Indonesia, India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and China.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rate of 9.7 percent, Thai shrimp products have
become less competitive than those from the above countries which
are levied at 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thai exporters are arguing against an evaluation by the
European Commission which considers Thailand to be better off than
Malaysia. Thailand's per capita income is 2,680 U.S. dollars
against Malaysia's 3,930 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Frozen Foods Association recently asked the Thai
Commerce Ministry to negotiate with the EU for restoration of the
4.5 percent rate on a fixed quota of Thai shrimp imports.
</P>
<P>
Thai shrimp exports worldwide totaled 161,486 tons last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Trade Robust in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade rose
by 13 percent in the third quarter of this year, the Ministry of
Trade and Industry said today.
</P>
<P>
In value terms, the country's total trade increased by 12
percent to reach a record high of 99.3 billion Singapore dollars
(63.25 billion U.S. dollars), the ministry said in an economic
survey.
</P>
<P>
The key contributor to the robust trade performance was the
sustained electronics recovery, supported by strong demand from
major markets like the United States and the European Union, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
This provided a buffer to the lower demand from Japan which was
suffering from poor domestic economic conditions, the ministry
noted.
</P>
<P>
During the three-month period, total exports increased by 8.8
percent to reach 47.8 billion Singapore dollars (30.45 billion US
dollars). Domestic exports grew by 7.6 percent while re-exports
rose by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, with the recovery in global electronics demand, in
particular from the major markets such as the United States and
the European Union, non-oil domestic exports expanded by 9.4
percent to 23.6 billion Singapore dollars (15 billion U.S.
dollars) in the third quarter, up from the moderate increase of
4.4 percent in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
While its trade grew strongly, Singapore's current account
surplus fell to 5.3 billion Singapore dollars (3.38 billion US
dollars) in the third quarter of this year, compared with 6.2
billion Singapore dollars (4.19 billion US dollars) in the
previous quarter, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Singapore recorded a larger balance of payments
surplus of 2.9 billion Singapore dollars (1.85 billion US dollars)
during the third quarter, compared with 1.7 billion Singapore
dollars (1.15 billion US dollars) in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the higher balance of payments surplus
was largely due to stronger capital inflows. Net capital inflows
rose to 4.2 billion Singapore dollars (2.68 billion US dollars) in
the third quarter, up from 1.4 billion Singapore dollars (945.95
million US dollars) in the second quarter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
