<HEADLINE> Highway Traffic Accidents Kill 30 Italians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of highway traffic
accidents over the weekend killed a total of 30 Italians and
injured some one hundred, Italy's state television station said in
today's evening news reports.
</P>
<P>
The past weekend saw the country's most serious traffic tragedy
in recent months, the TV station said.
</P>
<P>
It added that among those injured to death, most were young
people aging between 18- to 35-year-old, including the 1996
Olympic silver medal winner Andrea Masucci, 23.
</P>
<P>
The TV station quoted the police as saying that most of the
accidents were results of high-speed driving, especially when
turning corners.
</P>
<P>
It urged the departments concerned to map out more strict
measures so as to make sure that the drivers will drive within the
speed limit.
</P>
<P>
In late 1980s, the Italian traffic authorities set 130
kilometers per hour as the highway speed limit, but few drivers,
especially young people, in 1990s would observe the limit. They
prefer a dangerous driving speed over 180 kilometers per hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
