<HEADLINE> Surgery Restores Eyesight of Gorilla </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Veterinarians and eye
surgeons have successfully transplanted an artifical cornea to
restore the vision of a male gorilla.
</P>
<P>
This was the first such operation on a gorilla in China. In
addition to the gorilla in Zhengzhou Zoo named Nikou, the only
other such primates in captivity are his parents in the Beijing
zoo.
</P>
<P>
Nikou, a 15-year-old gorilla weighing about 100 kilograms
(220.5 pounds), began losing his eyesight several months ago
because of cataracts.
</P>
<P>
"It couldn't walk and climb as freely as before, and even
became fairly depressed due to the illness," said zoo keeper Han
Huaien.
</P>
<P>
The zoo invited doctors with the Henan Provincial Hospital and
two veterinarians from the Beijing Zoo to examine the primate,
beloved by locals as much as the giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
"It's very difficult to anesthetize Nikou because you can't
expect it to cooperate with us like humans," said anesthetist Zhu
Pingzeng, referring to Friday's operation for the primate.
</P>
<P>
Twelve zoo keepers performed 24-hour care for the gorilla after
the operation to prevent it from pulling at the bandages.
</P>
<P>
"We'll wait to see how the right eye recovers, and then decide
when to conduct the operation on the left eye," Dr. Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Nikou is the only gorilla born in China since its mother became
sterile after his birth in the Beijing Zoo in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Nikou's parents were presented to China by the King of Spain in
the 1970s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
