<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changchun New Tech Development Zone Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The New Technology
Development Zone in Changchun, capital of northeast China's Jilin
province, has maintained a dynamic economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The zone approved 170 technological companies during the first
10 months of 1996, including 89 hi-tech firms. Zone officials
expect to approve an additional 218 companies by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The zone recorded total sales of 5.83 billion yuan (702 million
US dollars) during the period, with pretax profits hitting one
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The zone plans to expand its total area to 10 sq.km., with
construction of an 1.25 sq.km. area already completed.
</P>
<P>
The zone will concentrate on the development of 50 major
projects before the end of century. The projects will focus on
automobile manufacturing, bioengineering, new materials
development, machine-building, electronics and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The city depends on the zone to promote the development of
foreign trade. The zone has attracted foreign investment from a
number of well-known transnational enterprises, including US-based
Ford Motor Co. and General Motors, and Siemens from Germany.
</P>
<P>
The zone approved 19 foreign-funded joint ventures in the first
10 months of the year, with total investments surpassing 96
million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
