<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Coach Looking to World Cup Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAPLES, Italy, November 16 (Xinhua) -- After beating Russia
last night 1-0 before a passionate crowd of around 80,000 fans
crammed into the San Paolo Stadium here, Italy has heaved a huge
sigh of relief and is now looking forward to the 1998 World Cup
finals as other teams seek to qualify on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As one paper wrote, Gigi Casiraghi's goal eight minutes into
the second half spelled "the end of a nightmare".
</P>
<P>
It will be the 14th time that Italy goes to the World Cup
finals (winning the championship in 1934, 1938 and 1982).
</P>
<P>
Sportswriters reminded their readers that a final score of 0-0
would have been enough to send the Italian national soccer team to
France for the World Cup but that last night's game was
touch-and-go virtually up until the start of the second half.
</P>
<P>
Italy's honor has been saved but many felt that despite valid
players, the team too often finds itself improvising on the
field. Likewise, the Italians cannot go to the World Cup with the
only aim being that of not letting the other guys score, Pistilli
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
Now that Maldini the pragmatist had made sure his team has
qualified, the 65-year-old coach has promised to experiment more,
modifying tactics and using new players as Italy takes on the
world.
</P>
<P>
Cesare Maldini, team coach and father of its captain, Paolo
Maldini, said today he would like to see several friendlies
organized to give the team added experience playing together.
</P>
<P>
In fact, a first friendly will be played in January between
11-25 and a second in either March or April. He is hoping for a
third closer to the World Cup, possibly around June 1st.
</P>
<P>
The Italians will probably be playing teams from those nations
which did not qualify for the World Cup finals, thus the circle
narrows down to Sweden, Portugal, the Czech Republic, Switzerland,
Ireland and Greece.
</P>
<P>
But if Maldini would like to test his players against
opponents from other continents, he could consider nations which
have already qualified, for example, one of the emerging teams
from Africa. This could entail traveling to Morocco for a game,
for example.
</P>
<P>
In response to criticisms that the games are not spectacular
enough, Maldini said the players were often too keyed up but he
snorted at those who suggested a psychologist be hired to help the
team handle the tension.
</P>
<P>
The idea of hiring an assistant coach has been categorically
ruled out too. The only concession Maldini is willing to make in
terms of bolstering his staff is to perhaps add an athletic
trainer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971117.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Pilot City Successful in Developing Export-Oriented Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong province and a reform pilot, has achieved major
success in pushing up exports and the use of overseas investment
over the past years.
</P>
<P>
The province registered 8,423 joint ventures involving overseas
investment in 1996, up 4.3-fold on 1991.
</P>
<P>
The city used 2.6 billion US dollars in overseas investment and
exports were worth 10.5 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 countries and regions have established enterprises in
the city, in addition to branches opened by 160 transnational
companies.
</P>
<P>
A constantly increasing number of overseas investors invested
in technology-intensive projects in recent years. The city has
approved 94 such joint ventures, cooperative enterprises and
solely overseas-funded companies, and has established economic and
technological ties with more than 30 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou High Technology Industrial Development Zone,
established in 1991, has attracted an ever increasing number of
overseas investors. The zone has approved 485 overseas-funded
projects and used 1.5 billion US dollars in overseas funds for the
establishment of enterprises in the new materials, energy and
bioengineering and other technological sectors.
</P>
<P>
The city's gross domestic product (GDP) has grown by 12 percent
annually over the past five years. Guangzhou currently ranks third
among all cities in the country in terms of overall economic
strength. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
