<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Husbandry Industry in Northeast China Provinces Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Three northeast China
provinces, known as China's grain warehouse, have emerged as new
production centers for animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
The three provinces -- Liaoning, Jilin and Heilongjiang -- lead
the country in the output of meat, eggs and milk. In the first
half of this year, the three provinces' combined meat output was
three million tons, a record high.
</P>
<P>
Two million hogs from this region were sent to markets in other
provinces during the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Northeastern areas have been important for commercial grain
production and heavy industry in China. Liaoning, Jilin and
Heilongjiang reported 16.6 million tons, 23.2 million tons and
30.4 million tons in 1996 in grain output, respectively. They
accounted for a major part of China's total marketable grain.
</P>
<P>
However, the economy in this region still lags behind provinces
on the eastern coast of China.
</P>
<P>
The three provinces in recent years have committed to
developing their animal husbandry industry, while relying on their
successful grain production.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning province had 2.25 million tons in meat output last
year. Annual per-capita meat consumption topped 62 kilograms,
higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
In addition, animal husbandry has become a key industry in
Jilin Province, accounting for one-third of the province's
agricultural output. Heilongjiang province is developing its
animal husbandry by adopting high-tech breeding techniques.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the growing animal husbandry industry in
northeast China has already attracted overseas investors, mainly
from the United States, New Zealand, Thailand and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Products generated by joint ventures here have exported to
markets in Southeast Asia, Africa and the European
Community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
