<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Teachers Urged to Earn Higher Academic Degrees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The State Education Commission
(SEC) is drafting a regulation to require college and university
teachers to earn higher academic degrees, in a bid to further
improve teaching efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The regulation stipulates that by the year 2000, approximately
60 percent of teachers in leading universities should have a
master's degree, while about 15 percent will reach doctorate
levels, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"The rest are required to have at least a bachelor's degree,"
Yang Chunmao, an official of the Teacher Affairs Department of the
SEC, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
For non-leading universities and colleges, the teachers with
doctorate and master's degrees will make up half of the teaching
staff, while the rest ought to have bachelor's degrees, according
to the regulation.
</P>
<P>
"The academic degrees of teachers in colleges and universities
in China are lower compared to developed countries," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that among the 400,000 college and university
teachers, only 12,000 have doctorate degrees, 26 percent have
master's degree, and the rest have bachelor's degree.
</P>
<P>
Key universities have already set higher standards for teachers
involving teaching and research programs. Taking Beijing
University for example, nearly 60 percent of teachers have
master's and doctorate degrees. In Qinghua University, about 72
percent of teachers have doctorate or master's degrees.
</P>
<P>
The SEC implemented a set of regulations for teachers'
qualifications in 1995, aiming to upgrade teachers' qualifications
in all grades of schools ranging from kindergarten to college and
university.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
