<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collected Dunhuang Literature Being Published In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- China plans to publish 35
volumes of documents and data collected from Dunhuang over an
eight-year period as a reference tool for Dunhuang scholars.
</P>
<P>
Hangzhou University, in Zhejiang province, one of China's
Dunhuang studies centers, will edit the more than 30 million
characters of collected documents and literature, making it the
largest research project in the history of Dunhuang studies.
</P>
<P>
The project is being backed by a literary, historical and
philosophical studies fund established by Tung Chee-Wha, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The university has gotten leading scholars to edit the works
and has consulted experts in the field from around the globe for
academic advice. Professors Huang Zheng and Zhang Yongyuan are to
be the chief editors.
</P>
<P>
The work will include collating Chinese books on Dunhuang that
are in Britain, France, Russia, Japan, Germany, and China, and
classifying them according to classics, history, philosophy, or
belles-lettres, says Prof. Huang Zheng, head of the university's
Dunhuang Studies Center. The first volume will be published next
year, said Huang.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang studies have been an international project, involving
linguistics, history, geography, religion, medicine, sport, and
many other fields, since the beginning of this century.
</P>
<P>
Many of the documents are in other countries and only a small
part is in the Beijing Library and the Taiwan Central
Library. Even getting all the photo-offset copies of these books
together is a major task. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
