<HEADLINE> Iraq not Want Military Conflict With US: Saddam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
said today that Iraq does not want to have a military conflict
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Saddam said during a cabinet meeting tonight that Iraq is ready
to address the problem of implementing U.N. resolutions through
dialogue while stressing that Iraq would not accept any other
solutions to the current crisis, according to Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leader expressed his satisfaction to the stance of
the international community and the Arab world in particular
towards the standoff between the U.S. and Iraq. He urged all
parties concerned to take the same stand on the issue and seek a
political solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq is confident that the international community
would sympathize with Iraq in dealing with the U.N. special
commission on dismantling of weapons of mass destruction in Iraq
when more facts of the issue are clarified.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting also discussed matters of international
reactions on the current crisis and preparations made by different
departments for a possible U.S. strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The showdown between the U.S. and Iraq was triggered by the
expulsion of six U.S. arms inspectors on the U.N. teams of
disarmament in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. resolution last Wednesday condemned the Iraqi move and
called for unconditional implementation of all related
U.N. resolutions by Iraq and demanded Iraq back down its decision of
expelling U.S. members of the U.N. mission in Iraq. The United
States and Britain have threatened to use force against Iraq and
their two aircraft carriers are on the way to the Gulf for the
purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
