<HEADLINE> US Urges Iraq to Rescind Expulsion Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
reaffirmed its stand that Iraq should rescind its decision to
expel the Americans on the United Nations arms inspection teams
for eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
At the end of her visit to Kuwait, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright told reporters that Iraq should implement all
the U.N. Security Council resolutions and allow U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) inspectors to go on with the work regardless of
their nationalities.
</P>
<P>
She said that the U.S. was looking for political solution to
the crisis, but she did not rule out military strike against Iraq
if the tension continued to escalate.
</P>
<P>
She disclosed the U.S. President Bill Clinton had contacted his
French and Russian counterparts Jacques Chirac and Boris Yeltsin
to persuade Iraq to back down the expulsion order of U.S. arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq expelled six Americans on the U.N. arms inspection teams
last Thursday. The U.S. and Britain are sending their aircraft
carriers "George Washington" and "Invincible" to join USS Nimitz
already there.
</P>
<P>
Albright, arriving here earlier today, was on a brief four-leg
Gulf tour which also included Bahrain, Qatar and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
She said the aims of her one-day tour in the Gulf was to
caution the states of the dangers that Iraq is posing to the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
