<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Brown to Oppose Plans for New Euro Club </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- British Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown is to oppose a Franco-German proposal to
set up an inner circle of countries to plan the single European
currency at Monday's European Union (EU) finance ministers meeting
in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports today said that Paris and Bonn want only
the countries which sign up for the European economic and monetary
union (EMU) at the start of 1999 to be part of the "Euro club."
</P>
<P>
The inner circle of EU ministers will meet for talks ahead of
the regular EU finance ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, Brown is expected to reject such a proposal because
the single currency is of "direct concern to all."
</P>
<P>
Britain, which has effectively ruled out participation in the
planned single currency for the next five years, insists that the
only decision-making body should continue to be the meeting of EU
finance ministers, or the Ecofin, said a Treasury official.
</P>
<P>
"Ecofin is the main forum for discussion of economic policies,
and the UK sees that as the continued way forward," the official
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
